A Republican Strategy to Oppose Obama's Reelection
Republican leaders justify their policies with the need to fight electoral fraud.
However, the Brennan Center considers the latter to be a myth, reaffirming that election fraud in the U.S. is less common than the number of people killed by lightning.
Republican lawyers have recorded only 300 cases of electoral fraud in the United States in 10 years.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on voting participation.
In this sense, these measures partly undermine the democratic system of the United States.
Unlike Canada, the U.S. states are responsible for holding the elections in each state.
In this sense, since 2009, the majority of U.S. governments have enacted new laws that make the procedure for registration or voting difficult.
This phenomenon gained significance after the November 2010 elections, in which 675 new Republican representatives were registered in 26 states.
As a result, 180 bills were introduced in 2011 alone, limiting the exercise of the right to vote in 41 states.
The new electoral laws require voters to present a photo ID and proof of U.S. citizenship.
In addition, these laws also shorten the periods for early voting, invalidate the right to register as a voter on the election day, and give citizens the right to vote for whom there is a court record.
Before the 2006 elections, no U.S. state required voters to show a photo ID.
Indiana was the first state to raise such a demand.
The U.S. Supreme Court confirmed the constitutionality of the Indiana Act in 2008.
The Republican authorities hastened to extend this practice to other states.
Over the past two years, they have promoted bills in 34 states that force voters to show a photo ID.
It is important to note that unlike Quebec, U.S. citizens do not have a universal ID card such as the Health Insurance Card.
In fact, 11% of U.S. citizens, i.e. 21 million eligible voters, do not possess a photo ID issued by a government agency in their state.
In addition, five million new voters in 2012 do not have such a passport.
However, it is often more than a hundred dollars to pay to obtain the required ID.
The new restrictions disproportionately affect young people, minorities and people with low incomes.
In fact, 25% of African Americans, 15% of people with an income of less than $35,000, 18% of citizens over 65 years of age and 20% of voters between 18 and 29 years of age do not have the required photo ID.
This is enough even further.
Students who are considered voters who vote increasingly for democratic candidates are not allowed to use their photo ID issued by their institution in several states.
On the other hand, the same states allow members of fishing or hunting associations who vote more for the Republican side to use the cards issued by those associations for elections.
Before 2004, no federal state required proof of citizenship for voting.
Arizona was the first state to introduce such a requirement.
Since 2011, a dozen states have passed laws requiring voters to prove their U.S. citizenship.
These measures are clearly aimed at limiting the Hispanic voices.
Because it is obvious that two out of three Hispanic voters prefer the Democratic Party.
Furthermore, Republican lawmakers in 2011 promoted laws in eight states that abolished voter registration on election day.
In addition, you have restricted the right of individuals and groups to assist those voters who wish to register.
These restrictions are not without consequences.
For example, voter registration campaigns in the 2004 general election helped register about 10 million citizens.
Because the measures adopted since 2009 have reduced the proportion of registration of new voters in 2010 by 17% compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican lawmakers in five other states have passed laws aiming to shorten the period for early voting.
For example, at the 2008 general election in Florida, 33% of voters who voted in advance were African Americans, although they only make up 13% of the state voters.
The same applies to the Hispanic population.
The latter made up only 11% of voters, but 24% of citizens who voted in advance.
In contrast, the whites, who represented 76% of voters, made up only 46% of voters who voted in advance.
Of course, democratic legislators and their supporters have strongly opposed the adoption of laws that restrict voter registration.
Several bills have been blocked by the democratic governors’ vetoes.
The U.S. Attorney General has intervened to suspend the most controversial laws.
They were able to limit the damage in part.
For example, only 16 of the 34 states have passed laws requiring the presentation of a photo ID.
However, the new rules introduced in 2012 will undoubtedly make the exercise of the right to vote more difficult.
Democratic critics criticize the party-political nature of the adopted laws and see in them as a clear goal to influence the results in the states that are decisive for 2012.
A 2011 report from the Brennan Center shows that those states that passed these laws make up 171 of the 270 votes needed in the electorate to win the presidency.
It is too early to confirm with certainty that these changes to the legislation on the electoral system will have a significant impact on the outcome of the 2012 presidential election.
But one thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on voting participation.
In this sense, these measures partly undermine the democratic system of the United States.
