The Higgs Boson Analysis
The announcement of the likely discovery of the Higgs boson caused some excitement last summer, and for good reason.
In fact, it is believed that this boson is involved in nothing less than the mechanism responsible for the mass of all objects in the universe.
And finally, it is the last particle whose existence has been predicted by the standard model – our best or “least wrong” explanation of the nature and behavior of matter – but has not yet been empirically observed.
But for the physicists, it is not yet completely certain that it really is the Higgs.
We know without the shadow of doubt that we have a real new particle, and that it is very similar to the Higgs boson predicted by the standard model.
Furthermore, this seems to be confirmed by new data presented at a major physics congress in Kyoto this week, but there are still no data to be absolutely sure of.
Nevertheless, let’s assume that it’s actually the Higgs, as there seems to be only a small risk of being mistaken, and let’s look at what it’s about.
There is a inevitable law in this world that makes it impossible for two objects to be present in the same place at the same time.
It is not possible to break this rule - and try not to do it too hard, as you will hurt yourself.
For even if particle physics is a really strange world, it turns out that such a law also applies to it: the Pauli's principle of exclusion, which states that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time when they are in the same "quantum state", where this "state" consists largely of some of their properties.
Based on this, physicists divide particles into two categories.
In one corner are the good citizens, called Fermione, who polently obey the Pauli principle.
And in the other, the Bosons are moving, a wicked band of anarchists for whom nothing is sacred – not that principle, which means that they can actually be in the same place at the same time.
These bosons, according to the website The Particle Adventure of the Berkeley Laboratories (which, by the way, is absolutely astonishing), are divided into two groups: the mesons that we will not address here and the "power particles" through which the great forces of nature spread and with which the Higgs boson would be somehow related.
But it must be emphasized here that these bosons are not all such exotic creatures as one might think.
If you are able to read this chronicle, then only thanks to a boson of extraordinary banality: the photon or the "light particle" that is the "messenger" of electromagnetic force.
For when a particle accelerates with an electric charge or changes direction, the electromagnetic field is "disturbed" precisely in that place, like a pebble stone thrown into a pond.
This "disturbance" creates an electromagnetic wave (light, infrared or ultraviolet radiation, etc.), and this wave is nothing more than a photon and thus one of the "bearers of force" bosons.
A more stable field
The same applies to the Higgs boson, with the difference that another field, the Higgs field, must be "disturbed" in order for that boson to appear.
However, the Higgs field is much more stable than the electromagnetic field; the pathogen must reach very high energies, slightly comparable to a frozen pond whose surface could only be crushed by a very large rock.
That’s why a giant particle accelerator like CERN is needed – the Large Hadron Collider is a ring with a radius of 27 km! – to such energies.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is again helpful in explaining the relationship between the Higgs and the mass.
In fact, not all particles and not all materials interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do this, but others don’t – for example, a sheet of paper would never hold on its own in the refrigerator.
And likewise, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those who do have a mass, while the others (like the photon, by the way) do not have a mass.
What can all of this research be “good” for, Ms. Plamondon asks?
For science, they serve to review the standard model (SM), and they also allow physicists to carefully examine any deviations between the observations and predictions of the SM.
By the way, there are numerous physicists who eagerly hope that such deviations will be found, as the slightest difference could open a door to a "new physics" and clog some holes in the model.
It must be said that the latter still has major shortcomings as it offers no explanation for gravity (ups!) and the dark matter that makes up about 80% of the universe’s matter (again ups!).
However, such deviations have not been found at CERN so far.
Impact of
The effects of these studies on the general population are more difficult to predict, but it would be wrong to assume that there would be no.
By the way: in the early 1960s, the pioneers of the laser in the Bell laboratories did not suspect that their work would trigger such a revolution.
They saw scientific applications, but nothing else.
In fact, the late physicist Willard Boyle - who worked in the Bell Labs where the laser was invented in the 1960s, and who in 1962 himself developed the first permanent spray laser (the first were pulsed) - has already told us that the laser was initially considered a "laboratory play".
Imagine yourself...
Additionally, applications can also result from all the instruments surrounding the research.
For example, in 1969 Willard Boyle developed a small light sensor during his work in optics.
Although it wasn’t the original purpose, this sensor now serves as the “eye” of all digital cameras around the world, giving him the 2009 Nobel Prize in Physics.
Of course, this does not mean that the activities of the LHC will inevitably change our lives, but it means that you can never really know...
Palliative care – the best way to die.
With its committee on “Death in Dignity,” Quebec has recently discussed the delicate question of the end of life.
The debate should be resumed soon, although a bill is being prepared.
However, there is still a lot to be done on this important topic.
Le Devoir has tried to look at this more closely.
A few weeks ago, Mr. L. was still living alone in his apartment in the Montérégie.
The prostate cancer that consumed him had left him a two-year period.
“They gave me five years to live, I managed seven years,” he said half-heartedly, lying in his bed at the home of palliative care Victor-Gadbois in Beloeil, where he had arrived the day before.
“H, it’s always a shock, you can’t be prepared for it,” he says.
The disease does its job: an immeasurable weakness prevents him from going to the toilet alone and even eating on his own.
Sitting at the table before a delicious lunch, he resigned and agreed to help himself with the meal.
Courageously, he even manages to smile and talk to strangers who are busy around him, bring him his medicines, and offer him a bath.
The courage of ordinary death.
“My greatest wish is that my diarrhea is cured, as this is humiliating,” he says.
A few hours later, the team found a cure for this evil.
“Over the course of our lives, we learn that a man pins while standing,” says Pierre Brodeur, a psychologist at Victor-Gadbois’ home.
Returning to childhood is an unacceptable humiliation for some people.
"It depends on the person's ability to take a step backwards," he notes.
Because, according to several people working in palliative care, major events are taking place amidst these downturns.
The patients who are admitted to the Victor-Gadbois Home for Palliative Care all suffer from cancer.
They have a maximum life expectancy of three months.
At this stage, they are no longer overwhelmed by the doctors and nurses who take care of them with so-called “healing” care.
For Mrs. A., 89, the worst fear is to die “consciously and by suffocation.”
But through the illness I really got to know my children.
“I have good kids,” she added.
"I don't have any more desires in life," she says before she accepts being put on a mask that helps her breathe.
In the coming days, she is expecting a final visit from her son, who is coming from Italy.
At the Victor-Gadbois home, a group of volunteers provide physical care and help with food intake.
Palliative care is used when there are no other options.
To make death more pleasant.
In Quebec there is a bed for palliative care for 11,700 inhabitants.
That’s very little, considering that one day we’ll all die.
Here life continues in the best possible conditions, explains Dr. Christiane Martel, one of the doctors of the home.
Both at the level of physical, emotional or spiritual comfort.
The dying person is given oral care with brandy or pepsi.
Diabetics no longer have to control their blood sugar levels.
Death is part of everyday life.
Last night we served Mr. X a beer who died overnight.
This morning his son will drown the beer at the feet of the deceased.
"We help relatives and patients equally," reports Nathalie Savard, director of nursing.
In the home of Victor-Gadbois, no day is like the other.
Alongside a 93-year-old man who enjoys the last family gathering in the yard and is well supported by his pillow while beating to his honor, a 36-year-old young man, surrounded by his parents, his wife and his two young children, dies tragically after trying everything to survive.
“For six months, three to five beds have always been covered with cancer patients under the age of 45,” says Dr. Christiane Martel.
53% of patients admitted to Victor-Gadbois' home come from their home, 47% from the hospital.
Access to palliative care
It is said that 77% of Canadians do not have access to palliative care, i.e. care designed to alleviate the suffering of patients when the latter have reached the final stage of their life, either at home, in a hospital or in a nursing home.
And several organizations, such as the Home Victor-Gadbois and the Society for Home Palliative Care in the Great Montreal area, are more or less exclusively specialized in the care of cancer patients.
It is precisely this major deficiency in Quebec’s health care that causes several doctors specializing in palliative care to face with concern the adoption of a law regulating assisted suicide.
Since the month of October, a manifesto has been circulating, signed by prominent personalities of palliative care such as Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Lapointe, to express their opposition to such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christiane Martel, Quebec’s healthcare system is not powerful enough to ensure that everyone has the right to high-quality palliative care before accepting to switch to death aid.
Recently, she says, I saw a patient who was in the emergency room for 14 days with severe pain without taking any measures to relieve her.
I fear that patients want to die just because they don’t get adequate health care.
And at the same time, several oncologists treat their patients, despite the worst forecasts, stunned until the last day.
Hélène Richard’s chances of survival were already minimal when she stopped a difficult chemotherapy.
When I told my oncologist that I was going to cancel the treatment, she replied that she regretted that I gave up the fight.
She told me I was at the end.
No omnipotent care
Dr. Martel believes that 90% of patients who asked to die thanked the nursing staff for not fulfilling this wish after their pain was relieved by a palliative care team.
However, it must be said clearly that palliative care in the treatment of pain is not omnipotent.
According to Elsie Monereau, head of palliative care at the Society of Home Palliative Care of the Great Montreal, 8% of patients do not respond to pain treatment.
At the very end of life, doctors often resort to terminal sedation, which results in sleeping the patient either sporadically or permanently until the time of his death.
We can no longer pretend that we do not perceive this side of suffering.
Patients without pain relief will more and more often have the opportunity to resort to this terminal sedation.
Patients whose pain is not relieved all say the same phrase: "I want to die."
But that doesn’t necessarily mean, “I want you to make me fall asleep,” but “I want my pain to be relieved.”
The realization of this report was possible thanks to a journalism scholarship from Canadian health research institutes.
