With Bitcoin, it is possible to pay and sell without a bank
The opposite of current monetary exchange based on central banks, identified transactions and processing fees between the parties.
Moreover, as so often happens in these technologies, there is a tangible political vision: the belief that the current monetary system, shaped by bank monopolies, leads to financial crises.
In fact, the Bitcoin invented by Satoshi Nakamoto (a pseudonym) is both a virtual currency (but convertible in dollars, euros, etc.) and a protocol for secure exchange such as BitTorrent, which allows for direct file exchange.
With 15,000 computers on the network, approximately 200,000 transactions have already been recorded.
A few thousand websites accept Bitcoin as a donation or as a means of payment.
After the price of Bitcoin reached a peak of $30 (23 euros) in June 2011, it fell to $2 five months later before recovering to around $10 today (the rates are listed on the bitcoincharts.com website).
Nothing impressive compared to world trade in real currencies or financial products.
Nevertheless, the European Central Bank (ECB) has shown interest in this in a report on virtual currencies published in October.
She describes Bitcoin as “the most successful virtual currency”, “competing with the dollar or euro” and “similar to conventional currencies.”
Bitcoin differs from other types of virtual currencies such as the “credits” that are used to advance in a video game that can be won or bought (and sometimes exchanged back) through games.
The social network Facebook has also developed a similar system.
However, trading is controlled and handled each time by a central authority.
With Bitcoin, all network nodes are simultaneously invoice keepers, auditors, money issuers, as well as buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Every transaction between two users actually takes place between two email addresses in the form of an email.
With the difference that the user can choose a different address for each payment, which ensures anonymity.
A number of data related to this transaction is signed electronically by a double encryption system.
This allows the network to verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Using the content of the file, it is also possible to ensure that the traded bitcoins are present in the public account billbook spread across the network.
The crucial step is to enter this new transaction into this book.
This is done through a mathematical task that is launched on the computers, with the winner, who is a kind of provisional central banker, possessing the privilege of adding that additional line.
It is a fragmentation of the file, i.e. the conversion of a large file into a shorter and unique electronic fingerprint.
The computers "take" the new transaction and add a number to it before the whole is "hacked".
The goal is to find the number that results in a particular fingerprint (many zeros at the beginning).
Once this number is found, the other nodes can easily check whether it is the correct one.
The transaction is thus permanently linked to the chain of all other transactions, and any modification would change the fingerprint.
If a fraud user wants to pay twice very quickly (less than 10 minutes) with the same money, only one of the two transactions would be validated by the network and the other would remain unlinked as they both have different fingerprints.
The computer that solves the task receives 50 bitcoins.
In order to prevent inflation, this reward will be halved regularly, probably before the end of 2012.
The bitcoins in circulation are thus limited to 21 million, but can be divided up to one hundredth of a millionth, leaving a certain amount of space.
In addition, the difficulty of the task increases with each improvement in computing power.
The life of the network has already had ups and downs.
The websites that provide services for Bitcoin were attacked and the Bitcoin deposits stolen.
“The exploited vulnerability doesn’t affect the actual protocol,” assures Pierre Noizat, who just introduced Paymium, a real-money payment company that uses the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also reports on the possibilities of money laundering using this anonymous service.
However, cash also has these shortcomings.
Major actors such as Wikipedia reject donations of this kind.
They are accepted by others such as the blog platform WordPress.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron of the Weizmann Institute in Israel analyzed the billbook and showed that 80% of bitcoins are not in circulation.
A mega final sale was launched in November.
“Thirty thousand dollars have been exchanged,” says Jon Holmquist, who works for the company Coinabul, which converts bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Noizat, who is also the author of a book on this currency, firmly believes in the potential of this technology as a transaction network.
His system, Paytunia, is equivalent to a credit card (with real money) or contactless payment with a mobile phone, but uses Bitcoin to validate the transactions that are cheaper.
In addition, the owner manages his identity and can thus remain anonymous.
The system can be easily implemented with traders, and the latter do not need to install new terminals or computer programs.
You just have to provide an address that can be “photographed and recognized” by a phone, Pierre Noizat says, assuring that he has thousands of users.
There is a common trend to rethink hierarchical systems in favor of more horizontally oriented systems.
“It will take some time for Bitcoin to prevail, but 2013 could be a turning point,” he predicts.
By the way, the ECB intends to re-evaluate the various risks currently considered to be high in the event of a success of this currency.
