A Constitution with the Breachstange in Egypt
This is a new poker game by President Mohammed Mursi.
While Egypt remains more divided than ever in terms of the constitutional declaration granting him temporary unlimited powers, he has decided to put everything on a single card.
To the surprise of all, he announced on Wednesday that the Constituent Assembly will adopt its final version the next day.
Just a week ago, the head of state had granted this plenary two additional months for the completion of his work.
Egypt has now been relying on a provisional text that has been amended several times for almost two years, weakening institutional stability and leading to legal mess.
This new initiative has only caused an even greater division of the country.
For his opponents, the president persists in his "autocratic delirium" by continuing to "break his word" and "step the right with his feet".
On the part of its supporters, it is assured that it is a way to end the institutional and political crisis as soon as possible and to accelerate the transition process.
A referendum should be held within 14 days.
A very short period of time forcing the brothers to give up their plan of explaining the text to the Egyptians section by section.
For the president, it is also a way to regain his public and democratic legitimacy as protests tumble across the country.
After confirmations in an interview with the American weekly Time show, Mohammed Mursi appears to be convinced that the Egyptians will vote benevolently.
Especially since the Egyptian people are given an ultimatum with this recourse to a rushed vote: "Either you vote for my draft or I retain the unlimited powers", the latter should supposedly end after the adoption of the constitution.
85 mostly Islamist members of this constituent assembly passed the text yesterday in a strange atmosphere.
The majority of the liberals did not accept the request.
Shortly before the constitutional declaration in mid-November, they turned away, believing that they were unable to put their views into practice.
Representatives of human rights organizations, religious minorities or civil society have acted in the same way.
In order to the decision capacity, 11 members, deputy members, were added in a hurry yesterday morning.
Some are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
It is not surprising that the articles were mostly unanimously adopted.
The commentators, by the way, found it entertaining that the only disagreement of the day ... was expressed in the time for prayer, as some members of the panel felt that the pendulum of the constituent assembly was not accurate.
The text, which was adopted last night, consists of 234 articles.
Article 2, which attracted all attention, remains identical to that of the 1971 Constitution, stating that “the principles of Sharia are the main source of law.”
The Salafist parties, for which the establishment of Islamic law is an important requirement, had hoped to replace "the principles" with "the rules", which would have made more stringent application possible.
For the Islamists, the fact that this article has not been changed is proof of their goodwill and respect for the other members of Egyptian society.
“Holyness” replies to the liberals, who see this only as a blow of propaganda.
Because, according to them, the Islamization of the Constitution takes place over other articles.
In particular, they have in mind Article 220, which gives the University of Al-Azhar an advisory function, in particular with regard to the verification of compliance with the laws of Sharia.
According to Egyptian specialist Sophie Pommier, this is worrying, as "the people who are called for an opinion are not elected and do not have any democratic legitimacy.
Here can be seen the first signs of a theocracy.”
The liberals’ fears are also fuelled by the fact that the next rector of this university is likely to be far less moderate than the current one.
“At the moment, there is no concrete religious commitment.
With this Constitution we remain within the framework of the civil state.
Most of the lawyers who have worked on this text are not Ulema, but academics who have been trained in part in the French system,” reassures Alexis Blouet, who writes a doctoral thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
He acknowledges, however, "that there may be ambiguity with regard to Article 220, since the terms used are borrowed from the religious vocabulary.
One refers in particular to the fiqh [Islamic jurisprudence].
And in the future, the question could be raised to what extent civil judges are competent to decide."
In addition to its religious aspect, the text adopted yesterday is heavily criticized for the extensive powers it grants to the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood argues that these are significantly reduced compared to the former regime.
Another issue is the powers of the army.
In accordance with the desire of the military, the audit of the defence budget is not submitted to parliament, but to a national defence council.
Similarly, there will be no prohibition of civil proceedings in military courts, as human rights groups have demanded.
The latter also share their concerns about the text they consider to be a threat to freedom.
The fact of blasphemy isined, and insults are now banned, which could have serious consequences for the right to freedom of expression, especially for the press.
Moreover, no more articles refer to the protection of women, emphasizes Heba Morayef of Human Rights Watch.
According to her, the only positive point is the prohibition of torture by Article 36.
This word was not included in the previous constitution.
While the Egyptian president had to speak on television last night, demonstrations are scheduled for this afternoon.
Supporters of the head of state will march on Saturday.
In Israel, Ukrainian tourists expect holy places, the navel of the world and a sea of sunshine
The Promised Land combines the glory of biblical truths, modern comfort and unspoiled nature.
AIF lists the top five reasons to visit Israel.
before the holy places.
Visit the Jordan River where Jesus was baptized.
It is said that all who bath in this river will receive God’s blessing.
Galilee is the place where Jesus performed his miracles: the transformation of water into wine at a wedding feast, the walking on the water, the shutdown of the sea tower, and the fishing.
This is where Jesus appeared to his disciples after his resurrection.
Most of the holy places are in Jerusalem.
Believers take the Passion Way of Jesus Christ (in Latin: Via Dolorosa).
The path begins at the Roman fortress of Antonia, Pretory, where the court was, and leads through the streets of the old town to the tomb church on Mount Golgotha, where the crucifixion site, the ointment stone and the tomb of Jesus are located.
Here, according to the Christian view, is the navel of the world, which symbolizes the salvation of mankind.
The Holy Cross Monastery in Jerusalem stands at the place where, according to a Christian legend, the tree from which the cross was made for the crucifixion of Jesus grew.
In Jerusalem there is also the most holy place of the Jews - the Wall of Lamentation, the remains of a temple destroyed by the Romans in 70 AD.
Traditionally, people of different faiths leave notes with wishes, which then go into fulfillment.
Take a journey to the heights
The ruins of the fortress of Massada form the remains of the secret hiding place from enemies that Herod the Great built for his family in 25 AD.
They lie on a rock wall in the mountains at 450 meters above sea level.
Only mountaineers can reach the ruins on their own.
Everyone else brings an airway to this historic summit.
In the north of the country at an altitude of 1600 to 2040 meters is the famous ski resort Hermon, which attracts countless tourists during the winter months.
From the foot of the mountain you can get there by shuttle bus.
The ski slopes have a total length of 45 kilometers.
According to an ancient legend, pagan gods allegedly lived on the mountain summit.
Visiting unique museums
There are almost 300 museums in this country.
On one trip, not all of them can be visited.
However, at least the five most interesting of them should be visited.
The Israeli Museum is located near the Knesset (Parliament).
There are stored ancient Qumran manuscripts or rolls from the Dead Sea found in rock caves in the Jewish desert, as well as about 500,000 archaeological and anthropological exhibits.
The Museum of Art in Tel Aviv is also worth a visit.
There is a collection of works by the impressionists and expressionists Monet, Pissaro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall and Picasso.
In Akko you can visit the museum at Bad Al Basha, which houses several halls of ancient Turkish baths with sculptures of the then visitors and bath servants.
In Caesarea, you should visit the unique private Ralli Museum, where you can admire sculptures by Dali and Rodin.
There are no museum guides or souvenir shops.
Entrance is free and donations are generally refused.
The fifth museum, namely the Holocaust Museum or Yad Vashem in Tel Aviv, tells of one of the most shocking chapters in history.
The most striking section is the Children’s Monument, built to commemorate the 1.5 million children killed in concentration camps and gas chambers.
When you enter the room, there is complete darkness.
The stars glitter.
And the names of the Jewish children and the countries in which they died were heard.
Ukraine is also mentioned.
Do something for health
The three main recreational areas of Israel are located on the shores of the Mediterranean, the Red Sea and the Dead Sea.
In each of the three locations there are swimming pools, water parks, dolphinaries and oceanaries.
Surprisingly, the Red Sea is also swimming in the winter months, as the water temperature does not fall below 21 °C and the air warms up to 23 °C.
The Dead Sea is even warmer and it is bathed all year round.
By the way, this unusual sea, with a location of 417 meters below sea level, is the deepest sea in the world.
Its turquoise water has a high salt content and thus carries even non-swimmers easily on the surface.
The surrounding landscape is indescribably beautiful.
Visitors come here for treatments using saltwater (natural saltsole) and medicinal sludge as well as to treat skin inflammation, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes, and to calm strained nerves.
Touching the Secrets of Antiquity
These secrets are hidden in the old town of Tel Aviv, namely the city of Jaffa on the Mediterranean coast.
Through this city, the famous sea route connected Egypt, Syria, Anatolia and Mesopotamia.
The city is mentioned in ancient Greek and Egyptian legends.
According to legend, Noah built his ark here, and Perseus saved the beautiful Andromeda here, with whom he lived a long and happy life in this place.
Tourists love to stroll through the narrow streets named after the zodiac signs.
Fortuna is said to be the legend after all who touch the walls in the street with their zodiac sign.
In Jaffa, you can meet newly married couples from all over Israel and even other countries at photo dates.
In Caesarea, the city of King Herod, you can stroll through the Roman theatre and conquer the fortress of the Crusaders.
In Roman times Caesarea was the most important city of Judea and the residence of Roman governors, including Pontius Pilate.
The carefully restored theatre now hosts evening concerts and operas.
Listings for tourists
If you’re traveling to Israel, don’t worry about your poor English skills: About 30% of Israelis speak Russian.
The money in the trip is preferred not to be taken in euros, but in dollars, which can easily be exchanged in shekels (current exchange rate: 1 dollar to 3.8 shekels).
The city is mostly accessible by bus, but there is also a high-speed tram in Jerusalem and Haifa is the only six-stop subway line in the country that connects the suburb with the upper city.
In fact, it is an underground railway station.
A ride within the city costs, regardless of the means of transportation, 6 shekels, which is enough including switching for a ride of up to 1.5 hours.
According to Jewish tradition, Saturday is celebrated in Israel.
From Friday evening to sunset on Saturday, markets and shops are closed, and public transport rests.
On Sunday morning, the working week begins.
In many cafes, restaurants and restaurants, only kosher food is served, which excludes pork, seafood, fish without shell, and foods that contain both milk and meat products.
Instead, you have the choice between various dishes featuring hammer and beef, soups and desserts (prepared with coconut milk), traditional Jewish humus paste, various sauces, fried beans and pears (Falafel), as well as fruits and vegetables.
There are no dogs in the streets of Israeli cities.
For this, there are many well-nourished cats that roam around the streets comfortably and unhappy.
In the evening, you can even see them sleeping on the roofs of parked cars.
Cats like busy places and don’t say no to delicacies.
A rental car costs between $37 per day (Hyundai Getz) and $188 (Audi A6, Volvo S80), depending on the brand.
The insurance costs an additional $15 per day.
And renting bicycles costs 15 shekels per day.
Entrance tickets to museums cost an average of 30 shekels.
in numbers
In 2012, more than three million tourists from around the world visited Israel.
Most adventurers and recreation seekers came from Russia, France, Germany, Italy, England, the United States and Ukraine.
From January to October 2012, 118.8 thousand Ukrainian tourists arrived in the Promised Land, an increase of 51% compared to the comparison period in 2010, before the abolition of the visa requirement on 9 February 2011.
"The Great and Powerful" Leads to Moscow: Migrants Save Money for Language
While MPs and civil rights activists are discussing the benefits of mandatory language tests for migrants, criminals are already trading with fake certificates.
Every year, 13 million guest workers come to Moscow, St. Petersburg and other cities of Russia.
Most of them are citizens of Central Asia: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan and Turkmenistan.
Their only goal is to make money for the maintenance of the families left at home.
On December 1, a law came into force, according to which every working migrant must pass a test that certifies knowledge of the Russian language.
Until now, this scheme only applies to migrants who want to work in the service sector, in the municipal housing sector and in the retail sector.
However, the tests will eventually become mandatory for all guest workers, according to the Federal Migration Authority.
This requires not only language tests, but also tests in Russian history and the foundations of legislation.
Language proficiency must be demonstrated for both obtaining and renewing the work permit.
Exceptions apply only to citizens of countries where Russian is the official language.
Also exempt from this law are persons who obtained their training certificates and diplomas before the collapse of the USSR in 1991.
Meaning, problem and protection of rights
All exams will be conducted under the auspices of the Pushkin Institute for Russian Language, the Russian University of Friendship of Peoples, Moscow State University, St. Petersburg State University and other Russian universities.
Migrants can pass the tests in all cities; more than 160 such centers have already been opened in Russia.
The initiative to introduce the tests was supported by deputies of the State Duma and the Federal Migration Agency.
Civil rights activists, on the other hand, repeatedly asked the press the following question before the law came into force: What does it bring?
What changes does the requirement to demonstrate language proficiency bring for both Russians and guest workers?
First and foremost, spokesmen of the Migration Authority respond, it is about reducing the number of forced laborers.
“Many are now talking about protecting the rights of migrant workers,” says Viktor Sebelew, head of the representation of the Federal Migration Agency in Tajikistan.
However, your rights must be protected before you leave.
Only organized recruitment will solve 90% of the problems of foreign workers.
Migrants face problems without work, education, language skills and medical examination.
Sebelew is convinced that a future migrant without language skills will inevitably encounter people with evil intentions, who, under the pretext of help, will put him in a dark, narrow barracks, where he will endure for dozens of months without food and documents and create 12 to 14 hours a day.
We get a lot of complaints from our migrants.
"In your homeland you are promised one, and upon arrival you are cheated, your passports are taken away and you do not receive the promised salary," Tolib Schwaripov, head of the head office for labour migration of the Tajik Migration Authority, confirmed.
Do not cheat, boss!
Nevertheless, many citizens of the Central Asian republics, who want to earn their money in Russia, admit that they not only do not master the language of the destination country, but also can hardly express themselves in their own language in writing.
Of course, this is not so much their fault, but rather the evil: only a few Turkmen, Uzbek and Tajik can afford even a reasonable elementary education.
Because in their families there is not even money to feed the children, let alone to buy them decent clothes, shoes and school items.
As a teenager, these children immediately take advantage of the first opportunity to earn money.
“It’s hard without language skills,” they admit.
“You feel humiliated and inferior.”
Civil rights activists emphasize the following important aspect regarding the law.
The test must only be passed by legal immigrants.
If you do not have this status, there is no examination and therefore no official work.
Meanwhile, most of the guest workers continue to stay illegally in Russia.
"Welcome" or "Entry for unauthorized persons prohibited"
Many migrants confirm that it is not easy to obtain an official status in Russia.
The reason is bureaucratic barriers and, of course, language difficulties.
In addition, legalization costs money: 12 to 16 thousand rubles.
A fake registration can be made quickly and only for one and a half thousand.
The Russian police know that most of our documents are fake and we are not registered, and this leads to cases of blackmail.
"They want one or two hundred rubles for cigarettes and tea," Umed Hushkadamov told reporters.
“Don’t pay for fake papers.”
Already on the day the law came into force, it turned out that not only the registration documents of migrants can be fake.
Some fake certificates certifying the passing of the language test have already been seized by employees of the Federal Migration Authority.
The fake papers were printed using a regular color printer.
Of course, the new owners did not receive them for nothing: every migrant who hoped to save himself from the tests, paid seven thousand rubles for the document.
That’s more than twice the cost of the official test: it costs a working migrant three thousand rubles.
That the most important immediate task is to protect the system from corruption so that certificates cannot be easily purchased, both officials and civil rights activists agree.
For now, the authorities can only promise guest workers who fall through the test for the first time to get time for a basic language course.
In addition, newcomers without language skills are offered jobs in areas where no active communication with people is required.
The Ministry of Internal Affairs ignores the illegal weapons market
The proportion of legal weapons in crimes is extremely low
The Russian Interior Ministry is planning to tighten the gun laws for private gun owners.
With this, the authorities respond to recent events: wounded in shootings at weddings and seven dead in the shooting of the Moscow lawyer Dmitry Winogradov.
Police want to ban non-lethal weapons in public and raise the age for possession of firearms from 18 to 21 years.
The proposal was supported by the Chairperson of the Duma Committee on Security and Anti-Corruption, Irina Jarowaja, and promised that the amendments to the Arms Act will be submitted to the Duma soon.
Not everyone is satisfied with the fact that the Russian authorities want to tackle the problems by "attracting the screws".
An open letter was published on the Internet, the authors of which - representatives of various weapons associations - urge the authorities to refrain from "senseless tightenings".
The percentage of crimes with registered weapons is very low, said the criminal rights officer, Vasily Lesnikov, to the Russian service of the BBC.
According to the statistics of the Ministry of the Interior, 142 crimes with the use of registered weapons were committed over the course of six months in 2012, while for the same period a total of 1,168 thousand crimes were recorded.
The authors of the open letter are convinced that a tightening of the law for private gun owners will not prevent criminals from using themselves on the black market.
Currently, according to the authors, in Moscow you can find every possible weapon for little money.
Meanwhile, the interior ministry stresses that the spread of illegal weapons is under control.
Suppliers: from the factories to the officers
The weapons reach the black market via several channels.
There are five such main channels, says a former Colonel Viktor Baranez, who worked for ten years in the Ministry of Education and the General Staff.
Screenshot of a website that accepts arms orders
The first channel is the army or the military, i.e. weapons stolen during the fighting in the Caucasus.
"The weapons were stolen both by the Russian officers and the Caucasians themselves," Baranez said.
On the second channel come illegal weapons, which are stolen from law enforcement officers by criminals.
Baranez explains that these include weapons stolen both from police armor chambers and directly from law enforcement officials.
Other weapons sold illegally come from military arms warehouses.
There were frequent explosions in military camps.
"There's evidence that in some cases it was firefighting to cover up the lack of weapons," the former military official said.
According to Baranez, weapons manufacturers also contribute to the black market.
"Today, there are countless private arms factories that cannot withstand international competition and therefore waste the weapons at hand on the black market, such as in Moscow," the expert reports.
Another channel of the black market is smuggling.
Especially many guns and guns come from poor countries such as Kyrgyzstan.
"There is its own, sometimes handicapped production, as well as a mafia that organizes the smuggling," explains the former military official.
Where did the weapons come from?
Experts calculated the approximate share of each of the five channels in the supply of illegal weapons to the black market.
In 2011, a report was drafted by the Center for Problem Analysis and Government Administration.
The experts analyzed reports from the Ministry of Internal Affairs and the Federal Service for State Statistics, criminal literature and publicly available data on portals on weapons.
The majority of the illegal weapons, according to investigators, come from the army and law enforcement agencies.
Half of all weapons on the black market are there due to "the fault of those responsible who have come to deal with weapons in their work," the report says.
According to the researchers’ data, 17% of weapons come from conflict areas, 14% come from theft in weapons production, and 5% come from illegal excavations.
A sales consultant at an arms store, who does not want to be named by name, assures that weapons found in illegal excavations have long been no longer purchased because they are outdated.
According to him, it is more common for merchants to obtain the surcharge in an arms warehouse.
A weapon, for example, a pistol type TT, is purchased through a funnel.
The weapon is exhibited and passed through the fence.
"The dealer brings the weapon to the city and sells it there for 900 euros per piece with two magazines," he says.
"The police, of course, know everything and therefore, if they can not comply with the plan to detect crimes, periodically conduct check purchases from dealers who offer illegal weapons," adds the sales adviser.
Like in a luxury store.
Buyers and sellers are most often familiar with each other.
I had looked at my websites and blogs when someone noticed me and suggested to come to the “Begowaja” station where a person would wait for me to take me to a certain place where we could then negotiate the price.
I only found out the price of the gun.
Military commentator Viktor Baranez
"To get a weapon, I need a friend who has contacts," says the sales adviser. "I have such a friend, but I don't trust him."
There are merchants in the markets, but there you have to go and make an appointment with a code such as "by Ivan Ivanovich, who lets you tell that the daughter has lost a tooth."
Currently I even get to some beatings about a friend I trust.
He also gives me the beats just because he knows I’m not beating him.
Newcomers are looking for weapons in different ways.
Former military officer Viktor Baranez attempted to buy illegal weapons in the mid-1990s when he wrote an article on the subject.
The schemes have not changed, according to him.
He got a photo album depicting “everything possible.”
“I felt like I was in a luxury store,” the military recalled.
