Šimon Ornest: In our concerts we want to collect positive energy
What do you think about the end of the world in less than a month?
This is one of those disaster messages that we humans like to jump to.
With our band The Tap Tap, we make fun of it and say that we are the only band in the world that can gather enough positive energy to stop or prevent the end of the world.
In December, you will also realize a unique project with three concerts against the end of the world.
Can you introduce our readers to the project?
This is a national welfare event that we have been planning for two years.
To do this, we want to leverage the marketing potential of the Maya calendar, which is predicted to end on December 21 at 11:10 a.m.
The day before, on 20 December, three concerts will be held simultaneously in Prague, Brno and Ostrava from 21:00.
The end of the concerts is supposed to be about the time at which the Mayan calendar ends on the Pacific island of Kiribati, which is in a 12-hour time zone ahead of us.
From whom came this idea?
Initially probably by me, then we designed the idea together with our graphic designer Honza Augusta.
Not only do we want to gather enough positive energy to prevent the end of the world, but we also want to think with the public about the state in which we will give this world to our children.
On the occasion of the end of the Maya calendar, we have also developed a unique collection of shoes, T-shirts, bags and keystrokes against the end of the world, with which the purchase of www.e-tap.cz can also support us.
The band The Tap Tap, along with other artists, also recorded the so-called anthem against the end of the world titled "The end of the world falls out".
Already today, the anthem is very popular on YouTube. Will it also sound at the beneficence concerts?
Of course, and for the very end, provided that everything goes well and the end of the world does not take place...
The anthem is to be sung by all performers at all three concerts at the same time.
In addition, the anthems together are broadcast live on Czech television.
The text of the anthem comes from Tomáš Hanák, who also plays the main character of Jesus in the video clip, also Xindl X sings with...
How did you get to cooperate with both?
We also cooperate with other personalities of the Czech cultural scene, which is related to the fact that we conduct many charity events and concerts.
We strive to engage these people intensively in our projects.
It has been shown that most people are interested in working with us and have fun with it.
What is the purpose of the proceeds from the concerts against the end of the world?
For the establishment of the accessible educational center Studeo, where we have been working for six years together with the Tap Association at the Jedlička Institute.
Students of the Jedlička Institute are regularly supervised by lecturers who help them with various leisure activities.
Since the students themselves do not have the means to visit the lecturers, we would like to help them in this way.
As part of the completion of the Jedlička Institute, we will build our own building, into which we will then move with this project.
At each concert, several groups and performers perform.
According to what criteria did you choose them?
We wanted to create a program that addresses all generations, including children.
In Prague, for example, Chinaski, Support Lesbiens, Illustratosphere with Dan Bárta, The Tap Tap, Marián Bango and Jiří Suchý perform.
You can find out more on the website www.kpks.cz.
Are similar “big events” planned for the future?
In May, we will perform for the first time at Prague Spring, and also for this concert we are preparing an interesting program with interesting guests.
Next year we would also like to perform at the Czech House in New York, and I personally – if we are in the United States – would also like to combine this with performances in Washington and Chicago.
Your overseas plans are not small, so far you have performed in Madrid, Brussels, London or Moscow.
However, The Tap Tap is a group made up of people with disabilities.
How do you manage these journeys logistically and organizationally?
It is not as bad as it seems at first glance.
Five of our members are wheelchairs, i.e. the wheelchairs must be carried in the luggage compartment.
Nevertheless, it has always worked without problems so far, ČSA and British Airways were always very well prepared for us that I have sometimes been partially surprised.
Even in Moscow, where we were recently, there were no problems.
Through your travels abroad you have a comparison of how it looks in the individual countries with accessibility, how to deal with people with disabilities there, etc.
How have you experienced these things so far?
After Madrid, Luxembourg, London and other cities where everything works better than in Russia, we witnessed that in the East everything is still in its beginnings.
In contrast to Prague, Moscow is absolutely not handicapped.It is still unusual for someone to travel in a wheelchair alone in the city center.
It is not even obvious that a wheelchair driver is presented, for example, in the elevator.
Fortunately, there are also associations that try to point out the problems of people with disabilities.
And in what respect do we need to get up against the more developed countries?
There are a lot of things behind us...
However, it should be noted that the improvement of the situation always depends on the efforts of the parties concerned.
In London and Madrid, it is absolutely common for people with severe disabilities to move independently in public spaces, go to museums, use toilets, etc.
It is not uncommon for a larger group of people with disabilities to actively participate in social events, but we are a little ahead of the West with the band The Tap Tap!
Respect in the public and accessibility is one thing, but only when prominent athletes, artists, actors, politicians or lawyers come from our ranks will things really start to change.
So far, these are only isolated cases of strong-willed personalities.
But if we go back a few years, what motivated you to start a band in 1998?
At that time, I started as a caregiver at the Jedlička Institute, where I met many young people who were interested in engaging in something intensely.
And since I am a musician and I play saxophone, I have founded a music company together with a colleague.
Well, and over time, as our moderator, Láďa Angelovič, used to say, something is out of control (laughs).
The band has only been known in recent years, or am I mistaken?
It is true that collaboration with well-known singers has helped us; in addition, we have also started to actively promote ourselves.
We have become aware that when one does something and this is not visible to the outside, one’s own performance in a sense does not exist.
Thanks to EU grants, we can afford good lecturers, high-quality equipment and so on.
Was it your goal to get it so far with The Tap Tap?
From the beginning, I felt the potential that things could be approached differently.
In the show business today, they often copy each other.
This is logical in its own way, since everything new is considered with caution and is only accepted after a long time.
There are few really unique things, and I dare to say that Tap Tap is one of them.
The first impression the viewer usually has is of course pity; that is only natural.
But this compassion is absolutely superfluous, because people with disabilities are not lonely and abandoned beings that we should regret.
They are people who can live a full life and develop if they have the necessary resources to do so.
I always say that when people with disabilities something, it is a progress not only for them, but for society as a whole.
Was it also helpful for this success that you are a strict boss, as you hear from many people?
If you want to do something well, you should not compromise on many things and also require some discipline.
In my opinion, this is completely normal.
Some come to us with romantic ideas, and when they find out that they have trials twice a week, have to go through preparatory stages, and spend a lot of time on concert trips, then the enthusiasm in many quickly fades out.
But this is how it works everywhere, in any band that works seriously and wants to something.
The Tap Tap currently has twenty members.
How many of them have been involved since the beginning, i.e. since 1998?
There is only one: Láďa Angelovič.
We are an open group. People come and go.
Anyone who has the will and the desire to participate is always welcome.
