Poland and space.
Last week, Poland was admitted as the 20th member of the European Space Agency (ESA) at a ministerial meeting, making it the second member of the former Eastern bloc (after the Czech Republic, which joined the ESA on 12 November 2008).
Poland began a close cooperation with ESA in 1994 and participated in several ESA projects in the following years.
Poland’s journey into space, of course, began much earlier.
Even before World War II, Polish space enthusiasts were engaged in space travel, but they did not always find understanding.
I recall here, for example, the lecture by A. Šternfeld of 6 December 1933 at the Warsaw Observatory, in which the author presented thoughts from his pioneering work "Entry into cosmonautics".
However, the ideas of the young engineer (born 1905) left the audience cold, and after years Šternfeld still remembered that only Dr. Jan Gadomski had shown interest in his work.
In 1934 Šternfeld won the Prix REP-Hirsch, funded by Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch.
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) later became a major advocate of astronomy and spaceflight.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish journals and wrote several books on these scientific disciplines.
Gadomsky’s world-renowned contribution to the development of space was honored by naming one of the craters on the Earth-facing side of the moon after him.
Already in 1925 a railway drain was built in Poland, for which a rocket drive was planned.
Unfortunately, the author of the draft and the details of this project remain unknown.
It is not even clear whether the rocket should be used to launch or to brake the drain.
The information about this comes exclusively from the contemporary press.
In 1933, the Polish infantry began dealing with missile-powered missiles.
The research was conducted by the Institut Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia in collaboration with Prof. Mieczyslaw Wolfke and Prof. Gustaw Mokrzyckiegi.
From the documents handed over, it is clear that the research has advanced to the stage of practical testing.
The research was then, of course, interrupted by the invasion of the German Wehrmacht.
In 1937, the draft of a photoelectric fighter rocket originating from Ing. Rohoziński appeared in the professional press, and the following year appeared the work "Rakieta - torpeda powietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza" by the author Leliwa-Krzywoblocky.
Both projects dealt with the military use of the missile propulsion.
Shortly before the war, all projects for the military use of missile technology were coordinated by the Temporary Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy).
The committee was established in 1937, but after two years of activity its work was stopped by the beginning of the war.
Further articles on space appeared in the Polish press after the war thanks to the work of the Polish Space Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
The first mention of this company is in the November issue of the journal Problemy in 1954, in which four extensive articles are devoted to spaceflight.
The article by Prof. M. Subotowicz contains the proposal for the establishment of a space company.
At the time, there were already the first projects on satellite technology, and it was expected that space exploration would have a future.
As early as its inception in 1956, the Polish space company PTA sought to join the International Space Federation, which was founded in 1951, and in fact the PTA became a full member in the fall of 1956.
The following year, the first PTA chairman, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), became Deputy chairman of the International Federation of Space.
He held this position until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, the PTA has participated significantly in the development of the extremely successful meteorological missile (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), the first Polish missile for scientific research.
The first type, the RM-1, was completed in 1957, the first launch took place on 10 October 1958.
The rocket with a maximum flying height of 1800 m was about 80 cm long and weighed not quite 5 kg.
Later, an improved version, the RM-1A, was built, and in 1959 flight tests with the two-stage rocket RM-2 began in the Błędów desert.
The rocket was 1.4 m long and weighed approximately 11.5 kg.
Another stage of development should already be able to do real scientific work - the RM-34 rocket should reach a height of up to 14.5 km and be used for observing high winds.
In 1962, however, further development was stopped.
The successor to the first RM-type missile was the Meteor-1 missile developed between 1962 and 1965.
The rocket was designed as a two-stage rocket, its total length was 510 cm and the launch weight was 32.5 kg.
From this rocket, three types (Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed, which differed from each other in the size of the transport space for scientific instruments.
The Meteor-1A rocket had a transport space of 0.4 liters, Meteor-1B over 0.34 liters and Meteor-1C over 0.62 liters.
The maximum flight height was 37 km for all three types.
Between 1965 and 1968, the Meteor-2 rocket was developed at the Aviation Institute, the first flight tests of which began in October 1970.
Meteor-2 had a launch weight of 380 kg and was able to carry a load of 10 kg at an altitude of approximately 60 km.
After that, the versions Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 were built.
Poland joined the Committee for Space Research (COSPAR) in 1960, followed by the creation of a national COSPAR committee two years later.
Poland also participated in space exploration with Soviet satellites as part of the Intercosmos program, and in 1978 the Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became the second intercosmonaut after the Czech Vladimir Remek.
