Argo: When it’s worst, call Hollywood
In November 1979, a mob of demonstrating Islamist students occupied the U.S. embassy in Tehran and held 52 diplomats hostage.
For their release, they demanded the extradition of the overthrown Shah Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, who had fled to the United States after the revolution, which had held the patronage over his regime for decades.
There was no positive way out of this situation for the U.S. government - it could not afford to throw the Shah overboard, as this would have massively damaged the trust of its allies in other countries.
At the same time, she was unable to enforce the release of hostages in Iran, where the revolution resulted in the establishment of a theocratic regime.
It was a heavy blow to the reputation of the United States, and the subsequent fiasco in the violent attempt to free hostages only made things worse.
The captured diplomats were finally released after 444 days after negotiations were mediated by the Algerian government.
The fate of the hostages sparked a wave of solidarity and anti-Iranian sentiment at home.
The debacle in Iran contributed significantly to Jimmy Carters’ defeat against Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential election.
The film Argo by director and actor Ben Affleck describes an episode of this story that gave the United States a small partial victory.
Immediately before the occupation of the embassy, six embassy employees managed to escape.
This ended after numerous complications at the residence of the Canadian ambassador.
The CIA, in collaboration with the Canadian authorities, managed to bring refugees from Iran, helping them with an extravagant story to hide their true identity – they traveled with Canadian passports disguised as members of a film staff allegedly attending the country’s filming for a science fiction film.
Combination of Genres
The plan developed by the expert on “exfiltration,” Tony Mendez, also required Hollywood’s collaboration.
In order for the embellishment to become credible, articles about this film project appeared in specialized journals, press conferences were held, and the fictional production company had a real office.
The details of this operation have long been kept secret.The film is based on the memories of Tony Mendez.
Affleck’s film is a special combination of several film genres.
On the one hand, he is a realistic political thriller, but at the same time also a so-called "Caper Movie", i.e. the story of a successful Hussar piece such as the film Ocean's Eleven.
As a result, the mood levels change in the film - on the one hand, the documentary scenes from Tehran (in the title sequence iconic contemporary photographs are shown, and even in the filming of the same situations there are no big differences).
On the other hand, the loose passages from Hollywood that come ironically and slightly overwhelmed therefore.
And then there are the scenes from the CIA headquarters and other institutions – men in costumes at the meeting table, on the hallways, on the phone...
Ben Affleck has made a remarkable start to his career with this film.
From a smiling actor he has become a respectable director, and even as an actor he is no longer the target of ironic remarks.
Argo is his third feature film after the crime No Child's Game (Gone Baby Gone, 2007) and the thriller City Without Mercy (2010).
At the same time, it is Affleck’s first film that doesn’t take place in the director’s home Boston.
The sense of the atmosphere of the place was one of the characteristics that removed the previous films of this director from the standard of Hollywood.
However, Affleck also demonstrates this feeling in Argo, where Tehran is "played" by Canada.
The best scenes of the film play in the streets, showing the reconstruction of events that really took place - the entry sequence of the messaging storm is very impressive in its clarity, yet conveying the feeling of confusion and unpredictability that occurs when the story moves somewhere.
Affleck and his team have achieved a similar effect on fictional scenes (the wrong film staple on a Tehran basar).
Too much action in too many places
The director also had to deal with the fact that the story does not actually offer many exciting scenes in the filmic sense.
With the few, however, he works quite successfully, sometimes following the reality - which then does not always seem so elegant (the scenes in which the threatening crisis at the airport in Tehran is avoided by a phone call in America, or even the pursuit hunt on the runway, seem somewhat artificial).
The weakness of Argo is its too wide scattering due to the need to show too much action in too many places.
Alan Arkin and John Goodman are very charming in their roles as Hollywood employees, but their characters deserve more space, and so they are far from alone in the film.
Affleck’s film loses some traction.It is a film that you can follow with some interest while enjoying the design and the retro style that reminds you of a thriller from the 1970s.
However, enthusiasm is difficult to arouse.
However, it is sufficient as a reminder of a piece of history that is still alive to this day and as a proof of how overwhelming the notions of the omnipotent and all-knowing intelligence services are.
