The server www.bankovnipoplatky.com, which annually calls out a survey on the most absurd bank fees, has decided this year to host the competition "Absurdest regulation or idea from the EU workshop".
“This idea was brought to us by the plan recently presented by the EU to introduce a 40% share of women in the management of large European companies,” Patrik Nacher, who is responsible for organizing this survey, told the newspaper Právo.
Among the nominated absurdities is, for example, the ruling of the European Court of Justice on the unification of insurance rates for men and women.
Until then, women had an advantage with life insurance because they objectively represent a lower risk for insurance companies.
“Other incredible inventions from the EU workshop can be nominated by the end of this year.
The actual vote will then be held until the end of February 2013,” Nacher said.
Among the controversial EU regulations are the mandatory mixing of bioethanol in fuels, which is consequently harmful to nature, the prohibition of reliable mercury thermometers only because they contain a relatively small amount of this hazardous substance, or the directive on the size of chicken cages, which has made eggs much more expensive this year.
Criticism has also reaped in the past the actual prohibition of the use of the term "butter smear" or even the ban on the sale of conventional bulbs.
Bananas must be 14 cm long.
The EU apparatus often decides under the pressure of one or another lobby from trade and industry, whose demands are usually represented in Brussels by one or more Member States (for example, the Czech Republic is currently trying to enforce the demands of Czech banks even with the threat of veto).
Lobby interests also stood behind the requirement that bananas of the highest trade class in the EU must be at least 14 cm long and must not have "curvature anomalies".
The European Commission defended itself by arguing that it merely harmonizes the disparate national standards that would hinder trade.
The standards on fruits and vegetables have already been softened by the EU against the resistance of some countries, noting that the previous directives would lead to food waste.
A candidate for the winner in this survey may be the EU regulation of last year, which, according to airballs, must be marked when sold that children under eight years of age are not allowed to blow up the airball without the supervision of an adult.
According to a U.S. study, balloons are the leading cause of child suffocation deaths.
A similar restriction already applies to children up to 14 years of age when using year-to-year trolley.
There are curious incidents at home.
Relatively absurd is also a directive that affects the European officials themselves – anyone who occupies an official position in the EU may not use the term Macedonia because of the sensitivity of the subject to Greece and must instead say FYROM (Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia).
The server Bankovnípoplatky.com, in cooperation with the association of liberal economists Laissez Faire, has also nominated the EU regulation on the amount of food supplies on the territory of a member country.
The EU has thus set the maximum amount of food supplies that could be on the territory of the Czech Republic on the day of our accession to the EU.
The Czech Republic then, for example, exceeded the fixed volume for mushrooms, for which we were threatened with a high fine.
The organizers of the survey were also impressed by the idea that certain countries should receive money for not having a sea, or by the idea of giving grants for applications for grants.
These ideas did not come from Brussels, but from Prague.
“We are disadvantaged by not having a sea.
We will apply for reimbursement from the EU,” said Jaroslav Palas, the then Minister of Agriculture of the Czech Republic.
As an argument, he argued that the grain harvest was very high and the state warehouses were overcrowded as a result of the so-called intervention purchases.
Since the Czech Republic has another route to sea ports, the EU should pay us hundreds of millions of euros, according to Palas.
The European Commission finally met the Czech Republic so far as to organize a tender for the purchase of cereals from countries that do not have access to the sea.
Subsidies for subsidy applications were offered to the municipalities by the Ministry of Regional Development under the leadership of Minister Pavel Němec (US-DEU), in particular the funds for submitting subsidy applications to Brussels.
EU: Bizarre regulations are the exception
Although regulations can easily become the target of criticism in the Member States, the EU’s efforts to regulate and thus to improve the effectiveness and development of the European Union as a whole deserve more recognition, according to some experts.
A more serious problem, according to these experts, is the EU funding for projects that have nothing in common with the deepening of European integration, but which were forced in the budget negotiations by individual Member States.
Emotions also highlights the fact that the Czech Republic, like other member countries in Brussels, must fight for the right to use specific designations of traditional products and does not always win this struggle.
Although the Czech Republic was able to defend the name "Olomoucké tvarůžky" after a six-year struggle with Germany and Austria, our manufacturers had to rename the inland room (Tuzemský rum), whose tradition dates back to the 19th century.
The term rum may only be used for products made from sugarcane distillate, not for products made from sugar beet.
In the official list of products registered in the EU, the world-famous cheese varieties Feta and Gorgonzola, the Lübecker Marzipan or the Parmaschinkens now include the Karlsbad Zwieback, the Karpfe from Pohořelice and Třeboň, or the Saaz Hopfen.
With an EU brand, the Pardubicer Lebkuchen or the Hořicer Rollen can be brewed.
