Szabo: “Germans need to play a bigger role”
Germany abstained from voting on the admission of Palestine.
According to Stephen Szabo, an expert on U.S.-European relations, Berlin balances on a narrow diplomatic level.
Deutsche Welle: Earlier this week, Germany had initially signaled that it would vote against the request for Palestinian observer status at the United Nations.
Then Berlin stopped.
Why Why ?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not support what the Israelis have done in Gaza.
However, Germany has to be careful because of its special relationship with Israel.
But at the same time, I do not think it supports the American position.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence, but without being too critical of Israel.
During the uprising in Libya in March 2011, Germany also abstained when it came to establishing a no-fly zone.
It was eventually implemented by NATO.
Is it difficult for Germany to take a clear position on important international issues?
Yes, that is true.
This is because it is just turning its foreign policy away from a policy that was so to speak managed by the United States, to a German foreign policy.
The worst thing is that Europeans do not have a coherent and unified policy.
The Germans are between the fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I think they are still working on their role, but they are on the way to a “normal” foreign policy.
A foreign policy such as that of France or the United Kingdom.
What does a “normal” foreign policy really mean from a German perspective?
It demonstrates the willingness to take positions that are independent of those of the US or European partners in the case of national interests.
I believe that German foreign policy is motivated by economic policy, that is, by exports and its relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
Germany’s economic interests differ to a certain extent from those of the other great powers and therefore Germany must protect its interests.
Have these economic interests influenced the attitude in the Middle East conflict and the vote in the UN?
First, Germany has large sales markets in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf states.
Therefore, it must be careful not to stumble the public, but also the elites, in the Arab countries.
This definitely plays a role.
But I don’t want to put too much weight on it, it’s not a completely one-sided relationship.
But it definitely plays an important role in German considerations.
Has Germany damaged its relations with the United States by abstaining from voting on important decisions, such as the vote on Palestine?
I believe that in Europe and even in the United States there is a great understanding of the German position.
That’s why I don’t think this was such a dramatic breakthrough as in the Libyan issue.
Germany may even have some respect for it.
Because it signals that as an international player, he must be taken seriously and his interests must be considered.
There are different opinions about the Palestinian initiative.
The United States has clearly vetoed.
Are there differences between the United States and many European nations?
Because of American domestic policy, these differences have always existed.
I think the Obama administration secretly has a lot of understanding of the European position.
But due to the political situation here, the government can of course not represent this position publicly.
I think the real differences are not as big as they always seem.
If you look at the relationship between Obama and Prime Minister Netanyahu, then Obama is not so enthusiastic about Netanyahu’s policy.
Is it difficult for Germany to agree on its close relations with Israel and the United States on the one hand, and on the position of the key partners in the EU on the other?
That is what makes it so difficult for the Germans.
It would, of course, be a little easier for the Germans if there were a coherent and unified European policy, which is not the case at the moment.
So they can’t be part of a wider line and instead have to push things out of their own position.
This is what you are doing with the euro.
I believe that in the future, Germany will take on a leading role in pushing Europe to a European position.
This is not easy for Germany, of course, because of the relationship with Israel.
This has always been a sensitive topic.
But I think the Germans are clear that they need to play a more independent role.
Does Germany see itself in the role of an important international player – does Germany want to take on a leading role?
Does Germany still have a difficult leadership role?
Germany is not used to it yet, which is still unpleasant and, for obvious reasons, it is still difficult for the country to play a larger role.
If we look at the euro crisis, for example, every time Germany takes on a larger role, various anti-German feelings are released.
This does not make it easy for the Germans.
This is actually the old problem: you don’t want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
Germany is in a much more difficult position than the United States.
It has to be receptive to various neighbors and opinions, and that is not easy.
Now the influence of the United States in European politics is continuously decreasing, but the EU does not fill this vacuum at the moment, who else remains there?
The Germans will have to play a bigger role.
Even if they don’t like it, it’s uncomfortable for them and makes them even more unpopular – c’est la vie!
Stephen Szabo is deputy director of the Transatlantic Academy in Washington, D.C., an institute where academics and policy experts from Europe and North America jointly research the challenges of the transatlantic community.
Szabo is also a member of the German Marshall Fund, where he has specialized in German politics, US foreign policy and transatlantic relations.
"Trademark protection" in China: When Puma and Armani suddenly become Chinese
Armani is a world-famous brand, as is Polo Ralph Lauren.
What is Armani Polo?
Behind this hides a name officially registered in China, which has nothing to do with the original companies.
Nevertheless, they enjoy protection as long as the actual names do not complain.
Even then, it is not clear if they are right.
“It’s becoming increasingly difficult for foreigners to protect their trademarks in China,” says Thomas Pattloch, a lawyer at Taylor Wessing, a law firm that specializes in copyright infringements in the Far East.
Every week a new case comes on my desk.
The imitators already have a few additional letters to enable them to register their brands.
So, Gucci is simply Lu-Gucci, instead of Prada, you are allowed to enter Prada-Kny.
German companies are also legally copied in this way, such as the sportswear manufacturer Puma.
Pattloch opens a folder with entries from the Brand Office in Beijing.
On 14 September 2010, a Chinese company protected the trademark Zegna DF Puma, an art name that was also used by the fashion house Ermenegildo Zegna.
It is well known that the Chinese are world champions in copying and infringing intellectual property.
In the big cities, there are multi-storey shops that almost exclusively sell counterfeits.
But Pattloch’s case is different: on behalf of his clients, he is opposed to the fact that Chinese companies are officially granted the right to use a name that is already protected elsewhere.
The Chinese call it “Bang Mingpai”, a passenger brand.
The word is derived from “Bang Dakuan”.
This means women who are fishing for rich men.
The Chinese authorities are not guilty.
"This is harmful to business, you have to fight it," Pattloch demands.
“The brand is drained, the exclusion disappears, the imagery damage is enormous.”
The financial failures and process costs of the affected industries go into the millions, especially in the case of expensive model products.
According to the market research company CLSA, China is the third largest market for luxury goods and the fastest growing with a volume of €15 billion a year.
However, deletions of dubious entries in the trademark register are difficult to and go into money.
The procedure can take up to nine years, with an uncertain outcome.
Pattloch reports cases in which the court rejected lawsuits because after the long duration of the contested name has become a "market reality".
