What are the main sexually transmitted diseases?
Bacterial STIs include syphilis, chlamydia and trippers (gonorrhea).
Common viral STIs include HIV, human papillomavirus, genital herpes or hepatitis.
Filter lice and scabies belong to the parasitic STIs.
Who are the main concerned groups?
Syphilis and trippers occur mainly in men who have sex with men.
The Robert Koch Institute estimates that at least four out of five cases of syphilis in Germany are transmitted through sexual contact between men.
In heterosexual adults, chlamydia infections, trichomonads, candidiasis (fungus), tripper and human papillomavirus are common sexually transmitted diseases.
The prevalence of HIV among heterosexual adults in this country is comparatively low – however: about 20 percent of new HIV infections fall into this group.
Chlamydia infections are much more common among adolescents than in other population groups.
According to European surveys, three-quarters of all infections affect young people between the ages of 15 and 25.
In this country, human papillomavirus is also common among young people.
How has the number of infections evolved?
Not all sexually transmitted diseases are required.
