Enrique Pena Nieto is facing a difficult start.
As Mexico’s future president, Enrique Pena Nieto, prepares to take office, Will Grant from the BBC analyzes the challenges he faces and the mixed feelings of his people.
Traffic in Mexico City is bad.
Even on better days, this is an ever-stocked city, but on Monday, a steel ring was erected, blocking several major transport routes into the capital and causing chaos on the streets.
The goal, however, was not to disturb people on their way to work, but to prevent protesters from reaching parliament.
On Saturday, Mexico’s new President Enrique Pena Nieto will receive the presidential bonds and take over the leadership of the nation.
He faces a complex task.
Under Felipe Calderon’s departing government, Mexico has been able to prove itself economically well, but the country is in the grip of a drug war that has already cost 60,000 lives in the last six years.
“My administration is strongly committed to reducing violence,” Pena Nieto told U.S. President Barack Obama at the Oval Office earlier this week.
I will propose a new security strategy that will help us this goal.
Prior to becoming president of the United States, Pena Nieto served as governor of his native state of Mexico.
In this densely populated, vast part of the country that surrounds the capital, opinions about the new head of state are divided.
A direct man
In the remote small town of Valle del Bravo, for example, one likes to remember him.
The residents of the resort attribute to it the development of tourism and the construction of infrastructure.
To reach the city, one can ride on one of the highways that Pena Nieto built, which is a great improvement compared to the brittle, holistic streets that once existed here.
Plakets with his name also hang outside a modern sports center and an impressive interactive museum on climate change.
"We expect real and lasting changes from him," said his friend and political ally Gabriel Olvera Hernandez, who works as a congressman for the party Pena Nietos, the PRI.
Specifically in terms of security and economy, we hope for an interesting and real change that our country so urgently needs.
After 81 years in power, the PRI was replaced in 2000 by Vicente Fox.
Congressman Olvera admits that after 12 years outside the presidential palace of Los Pinos, the party has high expectations for Enrique Pena Nieto.
The opposition’s accusations that the new president lacks substance, he rejects.
He is a very direct man, very committed and has great plans for the country.
He is a great politician, but above all, he is someone who can listen.
But on the other side of the state, not many people share this view about their former governor.
In Nezahualcoyotl, also known as Ciudad Neza, the contrast to the paved streets of Valle del Bravo could not be greater.
The place is hidden under highway transfers and in many ways represents a suburb of Mexico City itself.
And the problems in the community are of crucial urban nature.
Earlier this year, the military was deployed to fight the drug gangs operating in the neighborhoods, and violence against women is a acute problem.
On a spot in Brachland near a large garbage dump, the bodies of dozens of murdered women have been left behind in the last two years alone.
During the tenure of Governor Pena Nieto, more than 1,000 women were murdered in the state of Mexico – a statistic that even surpasses that of the city of Ciudad Juarez, which is notorious for its violence and murders of innocent women.
The critics of Pena Nietos believe that he has not addressed the problem of women’s murders adequately during his tenure.
But in the worst case, his government has closed its eyes to the problem.
In a concrete building typical of the downed neighborhood, Irinea Buendia struggles with tears as she shows me photos of her deceased daughter Mariana Luna.
According to the official version of the events Mariana committed suicide in 2010.
Her family believes she was murdered by her partner.
"When I arrived at her home, it seemed as if her body had been washed," recalls Senora Buendia.
There were signs that she had been beaten, and the body sticker had already been applied.
As her mother tells her story, a picture of Mariana looks down on us from the wall. It is attached next to a cross that carries a single word: justice.
But this, such as the family, has been denied to her so far.
The authorities have treated me as if I were a snooker, a disturber, a nörglerin.
They just want to accept their judgment and keep their mouth shut.
“But that’s not possible when there were so many forms and omissions,” she says.
When President Pena Nieto receives the presidential bond on Saturday, he also takes on a great responsibility.
Tens of thousands of Mexican families have suffered from violent crimes over the past six years, and the new president has pledged to take special care of this problem during his tenure.
"I hope as president he is as he was as a governor," says PRI congressman Olvera in Valle del Bravo.
But this is what the families of the victims in Ciudad Neza fear most.
Prosecutor says Bradley Manning did not complain about abuse
Prosecutors reject Bradley Manning’s allegations that he was abused in prison
The hearing examines Mannings time in military prison in Quantico, Virginia
The defence seeks rejection of the accusation due to harsh conditions of detention
U.S. Army Released Accused of Stolen Thousands of Confidential Documents
The prosecutor's office tried on Friday to establish that Army-free Bradley Manning - accused of the largest disclosure of confidential information in U.S. history - failed several occasions to complain about the alleged abuse he suffered in military detention.
At a cross-interrogation of Manning during a pre-trial hearing in Ft. Meade, Maryland, Mayor Ashden Fein explained that documents of weekly visits made by prison officials during Manning’s nine-month detention in Quantico, Virginia, showed no complaints about his treatment.
A day before the interrogation, which was held as a result of a defence request to reject the accusation - Manning had already been sufficiently punished by the harsh period of detention - Manning had stated that he had considered suicide in prison.
The U.S. military intelligence analyst, who was arrested in June 2010, is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents during his service in Iraq.
The material was then published by WikiLeaks on the Internet.
WikiLeaks has never confirmed Manning as the source of the information.
In Friday’s hearing, Fein and Manning reviewed the forms that officials had filled out after meeting with Manning during his detention at Quantico military prison, where he served under heightened conditions from July 2010 to April 2011.
The officials asked Manning questions and wrote down his answers.
When Fein interviewed him on the forms on Friday, Manning admitted that he had rated the treatment by his guards as "excellent" and the treatment by the facility as "very professional" overall.
The forms, Fein said, did not contain complaints about abuse, although officials had questioned Manning directly about his treatment.
Manning replied that he had expressed his concerns orally and that the officials had discussed them with him and indicated to deal with them.
"They wrote (after discussing the concerns) 'No problems' and that didn't necessarily mean I didn't say anything at all," Manning said.
The judge, Colonel Denise Lind, also asked Manning why he did not complain about his treatment when he met with a committee in January 2011 to examine the suicide thoughts he mentioned a few months earlier on a form.
Manning replied that his intention during this meeting was to lower his observation status to “prevent injury.”
The military said it had assigned him this restrictive status - which is one level below the risk of suicide - to protect him and others.
"I wanted to convince staff that I was doing well and get rid of the observation status for injury prevention (...) in order to a higher quality of life in my view," Manning said.
Manning said on Thursday he was arrested and transferred to Kuwait, where he was detained for two months before being transferred to the Quantico Naval Base prison in Virginia in July 2010.
He said in Kuwait he considered suicide and once lost consciousness due to the heat.
Not being able to know what was happening to him or to the outside world was stressful.
"My world shrunk on Camp Arafjon, on this cage together," Manning said on Thursday.
I thought I would die in that cage.
When he was relocated to Quantico, Manning spent most of his days in a small cell - at least 21 hours and often more than 23 hours - and without company.
He was only allowed a mattress, a blanket, flip flops, clothes and his glasses.
Manning said he tried to stay in motion because during the day it was forbidden to sleep or just lie down.
He always had to sleep with light coming from the outside into his cell.
When he turned around at night and the guards could no longer see his face, they woke him up to turn back.
In January 2011, Manning’s lawyer formally objected to Manning’s treatment.
In April 2011, Manning was transferred to the military prison of Fort Leavenworth, Kansas.
On Friday, the judge also questioned Manning on an accusation he had raised in his statement on Thursday — that he had to sleep naked in his cell in Quantico one night and stand naked in front of guards and other prisoners during a morning count.
Manning had stated that during this count he had never had the opportunity to cover himself with his blanket.
At the interrogation on Friday, Manning said he had concluded from an order from his guard that he should drop the blanket he could have covered himself with.
On Thursday, Manning said he had been forced to sleep naked the night before and had previously tried to show an official that he was not a danger to himself.
Manning told the official that he could have used the bundle of his underwear or his flip-flops to hurt himself, but he did not.
That night, Manning said, his underwear, flip-flops and glasses had been removed from his cell.
His lawyers hope that the judge will take into account at least his detention experience and will reduce his detention rate drastically if he is convicted at his military trial.
The defense has stated that Manning will confess guilty of minor offenses, while other charges that are considered too extreme will be challenged.
The hearing is scheduled to continue this weekend and the prosecutor’s office is expected to justify the conditions of detention.
The Pentagon remains in its position that Manning was detained in accordance with the regulations that apply to all prisoners held under the highest security measures in Quantico.
The charges against Manning include favouring the enemy, illegally publishing intelligence information on the Internet, transferring national defense information, and stealing public property or documents.
If he is found guilty of all charges, he risks life imprisonment.
The Mexican American Identity Crisis.
Many people are forced to leave Mexico due to the lack of opportunities
Mexicans tend to blame the expatriates - they remind them of difficult times, he says
Navarrette believes Mexican Americans are trapped between two worlds
On a recent trip to Mexico City, I had just crossed through the hall and had arrived at the passport check when confusion spread in me.
Signs refer to two rows: one for “Mexicanos” (“Mexicans”), the other for “Extranjeros” (“Estrangers”).
I stood there for a few seconds, not sure which to go to.
I grew up in Central California and was called “Mexican” all my life.
An ethnic abbreviation – just as my friends in Boston call themselves “Irish,” or my friends in New York “Italians.”
Later, I chose “Mexican American.”
This was Mexico.
And in my grandfather’s home there was no need for cuts or bandages.
I was just American.
I speak Spanish, at least good enough to assert myself in that language at both ends of an interview.
But I don’t have the vocabulary of a native speaker, and I don’t get rid of my American accent either.
So I took my U.S. passport and put myself in the line for aliens.
I thought about the moment this week when the future Mexican President Enrique Pena Nieto visited the White House to meet with President Obama.
On the agenda were all those topics that are expected when the heads of these two countries meet: immigration, drugs and trade.
Pena Nieto was also very interested in talking about the growth of the Mexican economy, which is one of the reasons why Mexicans are equally likely to stay in Mexico nowadays instead of emigrating to the United States.
He wants to allied with the United States and Canada and create a North American trade bloc following the example of the European Union.
And Pena Nieto vowed to continue the war of Mexico against the drug cartels, even though he did not give details about this.
Mexico’s relationship with the United States is complicated and full of resentment.
Most Americans probably never waste a single thought on the fact that the United States invaded Mexico in 1848 and forced the country’s leadership under a conspiracy to give them more than half of their territory.
But for Mexicans who think in centuries and not in minutes, memories of this event are not to be overlooked.
So as soon as a U.S. government official makes even the slightest criticism of Mexico, we hear — in the Mexican press and among the elites of the country — complaints about how the Americans undermine the sovereignty of their neighboring country.
And the children of Montezuma are on the path of war.
And yet Mexico’s biggest challenge really lies in the relationship with the more than 35 million Mexican Americans living in the United States.
Want to talk about resentment?
There is more than enough.
Mexico has winners and losers; people for whom the country offers opportunities, and others for whom it does not.
The only reason so many people of Mexican descent live in cities like Los Angeles, Las Vegas, Phoenix, Denver or San Antonio is that at one point in our tribal tree a person — a parent or grandparent — did not get a chance offered in Mexico and migrated northward.
And in most cases, this person corresponded to a profile - dark-skinned, uneducated, from a poor village, etc.
We are the descendants of these people, and our loyalty is to them.
Not in Mexico.
And although we may now live the American dream, have attended good schools and got good jobs, we should never lose sight of the fact that it is the American dream we are living – not the Mexican one.
Our identity may sometimes be vague, but when it comes to our loyalty, this is not the case.
This clearly applies to the United States.
In addition, we are aware that many members of the Mexican leadership do not like us.
This is based on reciprocity.
They see us as a reminder of a humiliating defeat and look down on us because we are not Mexican enough.
Our Spanish will never be good enough, our ties to Mexico will never be strong enough.
In their view, our existence is a symbol of failure.
If our families hadn’t failed in Mexico, they’t have left.
And then we’t see ourselves now trapped behind the silk curtain – with a pleasant life in the United States, but somehow lost.
My wife, who was born in Guadalajara and legally immigrated to the United States as a child, reminds me that there are tensions between Mexicans and Mexican Americans because Mexicans have a clearer idea of who they are – and Mexican Americans take them badly.
While she is a U.S. citizen, she sees herself as part of two countries.
But many Mexican Americans I know feel like they do not belong to one country or the other.
We love the Mexican band Los Tigres del Norte, but also Bruce Springsteen.
You enjoy the best of both worlds, but you are not rooted in either.
In Mexico we are seen as Americans.
And in the United States we are seen as Mexicans.
As I should learn during my trip, there is something that makes this relationship even more complicated: some Mexican leaders and parts of educational citizenship want to re-establish their connections with the diaspora.
They want to use Mexican Americans as temporary “ambassadors” for Mexico, representing their interests in the United States.
We are going to tell our American counterparts how great a visit to this country is and put pressure on the political leadership to intensify their ties with Mexico.
and now.
This will not happen.
Too many hurt feelings.
And given the unfair distribution of income, unfettered corruption and drug violence, many of us are not so sure if this is really a great country.
I am afraid you will have to go through it alone, friends.
That is fair.
If at least some Mexicans are still unwilling to forgive the United States for dealing with Mexico a century and a half ago, they must also accept that some Mexican Americans have a resentment for how their family members were treated not so long ago.
Hmmm .
Maybe we’re more “Mexican” than I thought.
Old battles, new Middle East
The ceasefire between Israel and Hamas could prove to be an unexpected pillar of peace
Can there ever be lasting peace between Arabs and Jews in the Middle East?
The latest bloody events seem to stifle such hope in the germ.
Amid the usual accusations, countless buildings were laid in ruins and ashes, more than 140 Palestinians, mostly civilians, and six Israelis were killed – and for the first time, rockets from Gaza have been hit near the Israeli metropolis of Tel Aviv and the Holy City of Jerusalem.
