Hosni Mubarak, the secular despot who ruled Egypt for 30 years until his fall in 2011, had little time left for Hamas.
In contrast, the brotherhood with Hamas is weakened and its leaders are more dependent on popular views.
In future diplomatic negotiations, Hamas could prove to be an actor that even Israel and the United States cannot push out.
Israeli hardliners, on the other hand, draw the opposite conclusion.
Hamas is no longer a threat.
The Israeli missile defense system, Iron Dome, has proven itself and many of Hamas’ missiles have been destroyed.
At least for a while, Israel will be able to sleep quieter.
Many European countries have blamed Hamas for the recent escalation of violence.
Israel has done well in recent years, especially under Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, who has largely ignored the peace process.
Although rockets from the Gaza Strip have killed about 30 Israelis since 2004, the country has remained relatively free from suicide bombers – not least thanks to the blockades that run into the West Bank and thus into the main part of a potential Palestinian state.
Netanyahu’s Likud party has allied itself with an even more militant group ahead of the January 22 election under Avigdor Lieberman.
Why do these insidious Palestinians hate them and leave them their own state?
If they actually had control of the West Bank,’t they fire missiles just like their counterparts in the Gaza Strip?
No, it’s better to keep them behind the wall and punish them if they dare to raise their heads.
Per the hardliners will be able to prevail, but the Arab Spring could make them a slide through the bill.
Even if the Islamists now in power in Egypt and other countries have little left for Israel, they will first focus on the difficulties in their own country.
Israel’s defense power is larger than that of its four Arab neighbors combined.
A war with the local superpower will hardly help the new Arab governments rebuild their economies.
That the pragmatic President Mursi has teamed up with Barack Obama to a ceasefire could be a promising sign – and symbolize the beginning of a new era.
Israelis should also think longer term.
While the rest of the Arab world is taking drastic steps toward democratization, Palestinians continue to be deprived of their right to self-determination – a powdered container that will undoubtedly explode one day in the Israeli-occupied territories, just as a bus exploded this week in Tel Aviv.
Repression is already undermining democracy in the Jewish state, and with the growth of the Arab population this situation will only worsen.
Bloody missions to repel Hamas in the Gaza Strip will increasingly demand their diplomatic tribute over the years.
Both sides need an outward push.
The correct answer is the one represented by the more reasonable representatives of both sides, the majority of the rest of the world, and by this newspaper: two states to which Israel covers territories for security purposes.
The – small for the near future – hope is that the ceasefire will give outsiders more influence to enforce this solution.
Egypt must now, together with Turkey and Qatar, halt arms deliveries to the Gaza Strip and is better positioned than ever before to convince Hamas of the idea of a Jewish state based on the 1967 borders, complemented by a territorial exchange and a common Jerusalem.
Outside Arab nations should also push Hamas and Fatah toward an agreement.
That would be more for the creation of a Palestinian state than with the upcoming UN observer status application.
Obama must also contribute to bringing Israel to negotiations.
During his first term in office, he missed the idea of his own peace plan.
Far away in the White House, it seems like he is also reluctant to participate.
But this is a regrettable, short-sighted perspective.
The United States has a vital interest in a stable Middle East.
This includes a peace agreement between Israel and the Palestinians.
Australian laws on uniform cigarette packaging come into force
Health warnings and sick body parts on neutral green packages that are the same for all tobacco brands
The world’s first unified cigarette and tobacco packaging laws have entered into force in Australia, replacing brand logos and colours with neutral, olive-green covers, which are also printed with dramatic images showing sick body parts and infants and children sick by cigarette smoke.
Apart from the different health warnings and images, the only difference between the packages in the brand names, which are printed in identical, small fonts, will be from next Saturday.
Australia has the strictest regulations for tobacco packaging in the world.
The Australian federal government wants to prevent young people from smoking by removing the glamorous image of tobacco consumption.
Studies have shown that people who haven’t started smoking at 26 have a 99% chance of not starting again after that.
"You can already see in young children that they understand the message that tobacco companies are trying to promote with their brand image," says Federal Health Minister Tanya Plibersek.
Although Australia has one of the lowest smoking rates in the world and the changes will only have a slight impact on multinational corporate profits, other countries are already considering similar steps.
The tobacco lobby fought hard against the law.
It said the laws would favor the black market trade, which would lead to cheaper and more accessible cigarettes.
“The laws will lead to serious, unintended consequences,” says Scott McIntyre of British American Tobacco Australia.
Chinese and Indonesian counterfeiters will offer much larger amounts of these products on the streets of Australia.
Others, on the other hand, say that the laws have boosted their business.
Sandra Ha of Zico Import Pty Ltd, a small family-owned company, notes that demand for cigarette tuis and silicon caps to cover intolerable packaging has risen enormously since British American Tobacco, Britain's Imperial Tobacco, Philip Morris and Japan Tobacco failed to challenge the laws at the Australian Supreme Court two months ago.
Zico has sold up to 6,000 units at wholesale stores and is waiting for new stocks.
For us, this is a good business.
According to experts, the hake in the popularity of social media lies in the exact population targeted by the plan.
A number of Australian laws have banned tobacco companies from TV advertising, prohibited them from acting as sports sponsors, and forced most retailers to stop interpreting cigarettes in stores.
The Australian government has banned online advertising by local companies and sites, but has no influence on international sites.
“Those who market tobacco and have only a small area left to promote their products don’t come around the internet,” says Becky Freeman, a researcher in healthcare at the University of Sydney.
On social media such as YouTube, Twitter, and Facebook, Freeman has seen an increase in reviews of brands written by “completely normal people.”
You have to ask yourself: Is this just a private person who likes Marlboro cigarettes so much that she even makes a video for it – or does a marketing agency have to do with it?
British American Tobacco Australia says the industry is focusing on dealing with the new laws rather than marketing.
It has even gone so far as to pay Ukraine, Honduras, and the Dominican Republic to challenge the new regulations – those countries complain to the World Trade Organization about unfair trade restrictions, although none of the countries have major trade with Australia.
A WTO decision is expected in mid-2013.
According to Plibersek, the government has held talks with other countries that are considering similar packaging laws.
In 2001, Canada became the first country to require photographic warnings.
In the meantime, it has been expanded to more than 40 countries, including Brazil, Turkey and Ukraine.
Harsher laws are being considered in the UK, New Zealand, South Africa and India.
Many Australian smokers are challenging.
The pictures do not affect me.
I simply ignore them.
"You just take a cube and put the box away," says Victor El Hage when buying a cigarette box with a photo of a mouth tumor.
Honestly, there’s only one reason I’d quit, and that’s my little girl.
James Yu, the operator of the "King of the Pack" tobacco store in downtown Sydney, says the unified packaging has made it difficult to replenish its shelves.
“I used to take an hour to sort a shipment, now I need four,” Yu says.
“The government should have simply completely banned cigarettes – then we’d have said okay, that’s it, we’re going to shut down,” he added.
In a constantly electrified world, it’s nice to be bored.
This Thanksgiving I unexpectedly spent five hours at the airport when our plane crashed due to mechanical problems and we had to wait for another plane.
So I had enough time to get a few thoughts to get bored.
I do not want to lie.
Waiting for a flight for half a day at the airport is pretty nervous—even when books, magazines, and iPhones (and, of course, tax-free shopping) are available.
But more and more academics and child development experts refer to boredom as something positive.
When it comes to them, it’s okay for us – and our children – to be bored occasionally.
This forces the brain to get lost in interesting thought courses, which may encourage creativity.
And because most of us are almost constantly staring at one or the other screen these days, we no longer benefit from the benefits of boredom.
So should we welcome the boredom with open arms?
and yes.
and no .
I will return to that again.
Like many people, I have always assumed that boredom is a relatively current phenomenon that has evolved with increasing leisure time.
But Peter Toohey, a professor of Greek and Roman history at the University of Calgary in Canada and author of “Boredom: A Lively History” (Yale University Press, 2011) doesn’t think so.
"In fact, boredom has a very long history," he says.
The walls of Pompeii decorate a Latin graffiti about boredom dating back to the first century.
And then there is the question of how we actually define boredom.
According to John D. Eastwood, an associate professor of psychology at York University in Ontario, Canada, the problem is that boredom has been defined and discussed in many ways.
After long reading research literature and presenting the idea to a focus group of about 100 people, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues came to the conclusion that boredom can be defined as the experience of "wishing to perform a satisfactory activity but not being able to do it."
Boredom differs from apathy in that the person is not busy, but wants to be.
With apathy, however, there is no urge to do anything.
The key experience of boredom, he says, consists in a “disruption of the attention process, coupled with a bad mood and the feeling that time is just slowly passing.”
Boredom can sound like depression.
But Professor Eastwood believes that although these two conditions may be related, bored individuals see the problem in their surroundings or the world, while depressed people see the problem in themselves.
Sometimes we think we’re boring, even if we just have trouble concentrating.
In their study “The Unengaged Mind: Defining Boredom in Terms of Attention,” which appeared in September in the journal Perspectives on Psychological Science, Professor Eastwood and colleagues point to an earlier experiment in which participants listened to a band on which a person read a magazine article.
Some groups heard a loud television program from the neighboring room that had nothing to do with the content.Others heard it at low volume so it was barely noticeable, while the third group did not hear these sounds at all.
The individuals who heard the hardly-heard television feeling more bored than the other two groups - they had trouble concentrating, couldn't find a reason for this, and attributed their difficulties to boredom.
When trying to concentrate on a difficult or exhausting task, the disturbance of attention can lead to boredom, says Mark J. Fenske, an associate professor of neuroscience at Guelph University in Ontario and one of the authors of the study.
On the other hand, if you practice a monotonous activity – “like looking for faulty products on a factory carrier tape – music can distract and help you not get bored.”
In fact, he says, we now know that cuddling around and cuddling, often interpreted as a sign of boredom, can even fight them by staying more physically alert.
“Studies have shown that children who are allowed to hang around learn more and retain more information than those who are forced to sit down,” says Professor Fenske.
We all get bored at some point – my delayed flight, a drilling speaker, a tired movie.
Some people get bored more easily than others.
To measure these differences, researchers developed a “scale of boredom susceptibility” in the 1980s.
On the scale, you can find statements such as “Many things I have to do repeat and are monotonous” and “I have so many interests that I don’t have enough time for everything.”
Using such scales, researchers have found that boys are more likely to get bored than girls, according to Stephen Vodanovich, a professor of psychology at the University of West Florida – as regards the need for more and a greater variety of external stimuli.
But in general, teenagers are a rather tense bunch.
In 1991, Reed Larson, a professor of human and community development at the University of Illinois, conducted an experiment in which he contacted a pager with 400 teens and their parents seven to eight times a day.
He found that 32% of young adults were bored at school and doing homework, while 23% being bored when they weren’t at school.
However, only 3% of parents feeling bored.
Professor Larson says today, 21 years later, he doesn’t know whether the percentages of boredom have increased or decreased.
However, he is confident that “youths are felt as boring,” mainly because children and teenagers do not have much influence on their day-to-day course.
So back to my original question: Is boredom healthy?
Sometimes not, because in extreme cases it leads people to take extreme physical risks and fall to gambling or drugs to ease them - this has been shown by studies.
On the other hand, many philosophers and authors are studying the relationship between boredom and creativity.This opinion is Professor Vodanovich, who has been researching the subject for more than two decades.
"With boredom, the brain wants to tell you to do something different," says Gary Marcus, a professor of psychology at the University of New York.
But the brain doesn’t always know what is best to do.
When you’re bored and you use that energy to play guitar and cook, you’ll be happy.
However, television can provide short-term feelings of happiness, but they disappear in the long run.
Those who give their bored child an iPad can help them get away from boredom, but they have not learned how to entertain or control themselves, says Professor Fenske.
And he adds, “self-control is transmitted from one situation to another.”
The child not only learns to talk, but also gets more self-control in other areas.
I don’t think we should celebrate boredom.
We should also not be too critical.
Instead, our goal should be to feel comfortable even away from constant activity and technology distractions.
Professor Eastwood agrees.
"It sounds like we have to be bored more often, but boredom is the tormenting, unceasing desire to do something meaningful," he says.
He believes that in truth people are only looking for a way to turn off and relax.
"In an environment where we are constantly over-stimulated, it's hard to get involved once the noise is silenced."
In Colorado, there is no clear guideline for the new marijuana law
The 19-year-old community college student and football player Anthony Orozco is facing trial in southeastern Colorado for a crime that will soon be legal in that state: the possession of a few marijuana pieces and a pipe with which he smoked them.
According to Orozco, he and some friends were driving a car in Lamar near the Kansas border on a September day when they were stopped.
After the police officer found marijuana in the car, Orozco was summoned for possession of drugs and drug utensils — cavalry crimes, each punished with a $100 fine — and was given a trial date.
“We are being treated like criminals,” Orozco said.
But is he also one?
In the uncertain weeks following the state’s decision to legalize small amounts of marijuana for own use, the response to hundreds of smaller drug crimes depends less on the law than on the location.
Hundreds of violations surrounding marijuana are already being abandoned here and in the state of Washington, which has approved similar measures.
Police will no longer prosecute adults over the age of 21 for small-scale possessions, which will be legally permitted as soon as the new laws come into force in the coming weeks.
But prosecutors in the more conservative districts of Colorado have announced that they will continue to prosecute existing marijuana offenses and are still quoting people in court.
At the same time, several cities, from the suburbs of Denver to the Western Mountains, are voting to prevent new, government-licensed marijuana stores from opening in their communities.
“This situation is developing so quickly that I don’t even know what will happen next,” said Daniel J. Oates, chief of police in Aurora, east of Denver.
Even regulators in the state of Washington are scratching their heads.
They are waiting for guidance to establish a licensing system for the production, manufacture, distribution and sale of the drug - with a deadline until December 1, 2013.
In Washington, it is believed that Colorado in any case is ahead of most states in regards to the regulation of marijuana.
"Colorado has a more regulated market, so the state is well suited for guidance," says Brian E. Smith, spokesman for the Washington State Spirits Regulatory Authority.
But Smith also admits that no place or system can do more than serve in the sense of a rough guide.
“We don’t have a real precedent that we can follow,” he added.
The Washington Act, called I-502, comes into force on December 6 and thus also forms the endpoint of a gray zone in which the state licensing system does not yet exist, but possession is legalized.
And unpleasant practical issues need to be clarified during this time—such as how to agree on the state’s requirement of “adequate access” to licensed marijuana with the ban on cannabis stores within 300 meters of schools, parks, playgrounds and child care facilities.
“Nowhere will it be harder to find a location for a licensed cannabis business than in urban areas, especially in the urban area of Seattle,” said Ben Livingston, spokesman for the Center for Legal Cannabis, a newly formed research group.
On November 21, Chief Oates sent an email to his employees in Aurora stating that the prosecutor would no longer prosecute minor marijuana offenses against people over 21 and that the police “from now on” would not seek criminal charges for these offenses.
Chief Oates added that police will continue to enforce city regulations regulating medical marijuana growers and drug dealers will continue to be prosecuted.
In Weld County, northern Colorado, District Attorney Ken Buck has a stricter view.
After the vote, he said his authority would continue to pursue cases of marijuana possession, mainly to move consumers to withdraw.
Currently, 119 people have been charged with possession of about 50 grams or less of marijuana, although many have also been charged with other crimes.
“Our authority has the duty to prosecute violations that were criminal at the time of the crime,” Buck said in a statement.
The reactions are ambiguous even in places like rural Mesa County, where voters rejected the marijuana initiative.
Police in Grand Junction, the county’s largest city, no longer show adults for possessing smaller amounts.
District Attorney Pete Hautzinger supported this decision, but also decided not to drop all outstanding ownership proceedings.
“I don’t think I’m wasting my time enforcing the law until it changes,” he says.
Although 55% of Colorado voters supported the measure, it was clear from the outset that it would not be easy to reconcile personal marijuana consumption with the complexities of government and legal system.
And the contradictory reactions across the state sparked a deep divide among local officials regarding the big green experiment.
District prosecutors are a “cultural barrier,” says Sean McAllister, a Denver lawyer who represents defendants in court for marijuana crimes and acts on the spot as a spokesman for the national organization to reform marijuana laws.
“They’ve spent so much of their lives prosecuting people for still unable to accept legalization,” he believes.
As the first states to treat smaller amounts of marijuana like alcohol, Colorado and Washington are being treated as national model cases for legalizing drugs.
While advocates and government officials are preparing for an era of legal sale, they are also nervously waiting for instructions from the federal government, which wants to continue to treat the sale and cultivation of marijuana at the federal level as a crime.
Proponents of the legalization movement hope that the Ministry of Justice will surrender.
Despite several alarming arrests of consumers and sellers of medical marijuana, the federal government has largely allowed the sale of medical marijuana in Colorado, Washington, and 16 other states.
Kevin A. Sabet, a former drug policy adviser for the Obama administration, believes that while criminal officers are unlikely to enter doors to seize smaller amounts of the drugs, they are likely to strive to tolerate legal, state-regulated marijuana under the new legislation.
Several cities in Colorado are not waiting for federal authorities to act.
Even before the election day, some local municipalities approved moratoriums on new marijuana stores, although these may not open in about a year.
Last week, Montrose, a city in the west, decided on a six-month ban, which is likely to be passed next week.
“We don’t want to get into a position where we license someone and then face a big problem at federal level,” said Bob Nicholson, a city council member.
Our municipality voted against this legislative amendment.
We are guided by what the community has chosen, not by what the state has chosen.
A lot of questions remain open.
Petronella Wyatt: I was bullied from Oxford because I am Tory
Not only today’s university students are being attacked for their views
It has always been my biggest dream to get a place at Oxford University.
Both my father and my older brother had attended that university, which I once considered the greatest seat of knowledge in the world, for a modern Greek symposium that promoted the great pillars of civilization – free thought and tolerance.
But within two weeks of entering Worscester College in the late 1980s – where I had planned to study history – I had packed my suitcases again, causing the first scandal of my life.
My father broke up in tears.
My friends were confused.
In the Evening Standard it was said I had left because I had a problem with fellow classmates having sex in the neighboring room.
Author A. N. Wilson sadly stated that I had left the university because I was forced to drink from damaged cups.
But the truth was less fun.
I ran away.
Yes, I ran because I suffered from systematic bullying and threats.
Not because of my quite unusual name, or because I came from a private school.
I had only been harassed for one reason—a reason that seemed so narrow-minded and cruel in this supposed cradle of enlightenment: my now dead father, Woodrow Wyatt, had been an important adviser to Margaret Thatcher, and I was a supporter of the Conservative Party.
Why am I mentioning this right now?
Now, according to recent reports, a new generation of moderate-right students is suffering from similar persecution.
The organized and growing hatred of Tory students in Oxford has now developed such dimensions that a group of them last week called for the same equal protection that benefits gay, disabled and ethnic minorities.
Conservative members of the Corpus Christi College’s Junior Common Room (JCR) say they are “often actively isolated, personally attacked and declared unwanted” due to their political views.
They demand a seat in their college’s equality committee to ensure that their opinions can be freely expressed.
Their situation has been aggravated by a recent documentary about political students on BBC Two, "Wonderland: Young, Bright and on the Right," depicting the Tories as eccentric and neo-Nazis.
It showed, among other things, graduate Joe Cooke, former president of the Conservative Student Association of the University of Oxford, who was driving a Rolls-Royce and wore a silver costume and a silver-covered pedestal.
At other universities, conservative students say they are seen as “punishments for introducing higher tuition fees.”
Luke Black, 20, vice president of the Conservative Student Association at the University of Nottingham, said in a Sunday newspaper: “There is a growing leftist trend at universities.
“People think we’re like the Bullingdon Club without ever getting to know us.”
Samuel Roberts, 21, and a history student at Corpus Christi, who initiated the request for greater protection, considers such a climate to be "unpleasant." 19-year-old Stephanie Cherill, appointed president of the Oxford Conservative Student Association, says she has seen a growing rejection of moderate-right students among JCR members.
“This poses a danger to the intellectual discourse and the well-being of the members,” she says.
In my first weeks at Oxford, I belonged to such a minority.
As an incredibly shy 18-year-old, I had arrived in September 1986.
The hatred of the Conservative Party had reached its peak.
Last year, the university voted not to award Margaret Thatcher – a former student – an honorary title due to cuts in university education.
The atmosphere would have scared even the Stalinists.
In the first days of the first semester week, when new students get to know each other and the tutors, I got a taste of what was going to happen in the future.
I had the experience that the tutors not only tolerated the ridicule of Tory students, but even joined them with pleasure.
Political topics such as the miners’ strike, privatization and the government’s rejection of sanctions against South Africa’s apartheid regime found their way into the wooden rooms of the tutorial.
At my first of these events, I had to translate French texts from the 18th century into English.
"Miss Wyatt," said tutor Harry Pitt (now dead), "please translate the first paragraph."
I stumbled at it.
Pitt was a small man with a face like chicken, and quite disgusting.
"Do Thatcher supporters refuse to learn French, or are they just stupid?" he asked me.
The other students stumbled.
In my eyes were tears.
“I suggest that they take a few French lessons in your free time – so if you’re not too busy with your social activities,” Pitt nodded to me.
I went back to my room with my head hanging.
That evening I was sitting alone at college for dinner when someone slightly tapped me on my shoulder.
There was an English second-year student named James who presented himself as a member of the Conservative Student Association.
“I know who you are,” he said kindly.
Unfortunately it is as it is.
Anyone who is suspected of being Tory is harassed.
It’s bad enough for me, but they know your father Margaret Thatcher is close, so it’s going to be worse for you.
Most Tory first-semesterers pretend to be supporters of the Labour Party.
In a local pub, I later tried to get distracted.
I insisted that I did not agree with Mrs. Thatcher on all points.
This trick should prove to be unsuccessful.
A graduate of philosophy, politics and economics who, ironically, attended Eton College, considered conservative, said to me, “You are the daughter of a fascist pig.”
You are contaminated.
Other students shared his opinion.
I was perverse and dirty.
“How do Tories have sex?” one asked me.
They are fighting each other, right?
I felt what homosexuals must have felt before the more liberal legislation of the United States.
Would I ever be able to live a normal life at Oxford University?
Would I be able to meet like-minded people only after darkness?
Should I turn to the Labour Party and suppress my natural inclinations?
The three years ahead of me stretched out in front of my spiritual eye into a fire of rejection and isolation.
The only tutor who openly recognized himself as Tory was Norman Stone, a professor of contemporary history, who had his seat in my college.
He was hated not only for being a conservative, but also for advising and writing speeches for Thatcher on foreign policy matters.
He was rarely there.
He hated the place, found it provincial and small-carried, and rejected it for its Marxist-determinist historical perspective.
In 1997 he accepted a professorship at Bilkent University in Ankara, Turkey.
“You won’t be happy here,” he said.
I started pending between Oxford and my parents’ home and found refuge with more open friends and family members in the city.
I told my father that I hated Oxford, and why I did.
He seemed unbelieving.
During his time in the forties, all political views were accepted.
“But it’s the best place in the world,” he said softly.
Such a thing they would never do, not in my city of dreaming tower tops.
Even my communist friends always displayed improper manners.
His damp eyes blurred.
Give the whole a chance.
I’m sure they just cheat you.
It would break my heart if you left.
Exhausted by my frequent trips to London, my emotional resistance became weaker.
One of my male friends, also a Tory supporter, had surrendered to pressure and abandoned his beliefs.
During a tutorial the following week, where another historian had seriously claimed that I was “an enemy of the people,” I decided to do the same.
Though I was secretly scattered by shame, I admitted that my parents had undergone me a "brainwash" and called it "old fool."
The relief lasted only a short time.
It was my father who hit the last nail in the coffin of my Oxford career.
At that time, he wrote two columns a week in the Murdoch press.
My door was locked.
I hid in my room, and after five minutes my hats gave up.
As they went, I packed a suitcase and took the first train to London.
I never returned.
You can call me a crapper.
But no 18-year-old should ever have to suffer such intimidation and malice in an educational institution.
And even more tragic, it was Oxford – a university that not only produced 14 Tory prime ministers, but hides itself to this day behind an unmerited reputation for equality and freedom of thought.
