The Most Difficult Profession in the World: The Human Working Animals by Kawah Ijen
For four euros, the carriers of the Indonesian volcano risk their lives and health by carrying 70 kilos of sulfur across the steep, rocky paths.
There are people for whom their work is hell, and others literally work in hell.
This is the case with Anto Wijaya, one of the 400 miners who earn their lives by harvesting sulfur from the Kawah Ijen volcano in the east of the Indonesian island of Java.
To do this, it has to climb down to the bottom of its crater every day, where the sulfur-containing gas that flows out of the earth solidifies in contact with the air.
After breaking out large sulfur stones that can weigh up to 70 kilograms in total, he transports them in two bamboo baskets on his shoulders across the descending stone paths.
While it’s only 250 meters to the top of the volcano, which rises to an altitude of 2,386 meters, the exhausted carriers need more than 40 minutes to climb at the turtle’s pace while keeping the balance and taking their steps carefully so they don’t slip out and crash.
They know that every step can cost their lives, as it happened to a French tourist who crashed on the slopes of the Kawah Ijen years ago.
The miners at Kawah Ijen earn 5 euro cents for every kilogram of sulfur they mine.
Arriving above, they pave the way between the tourists who photograph them like circus monkeys and run with the exhaustingly heavy baskets three kilometers to the scale that a mining company has set up a little further down at an altitude of 1850 meters.
The company is PT Candi Ngrimbi, which has been exploiting the volcano’s reservoirs since 1960 and (never to say better) its workers, to whom it pays 662 Indonesian rupees (5 euro cents) for every kilogram of sulfur.
They then sell it to the petrochemical industry for 10,000 rupees (83 cents) each, because this mineral is widely used in everyday life and is used for the manufacture of timber, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even to whiten sugar.
"Since we normally carry 70 kg, we get about 46,000 rupees (3.8 euros) for each route," explains Anto, who normally does three routes a day.
For each route he needs three hours, after which he is completely done, but at the end of the day he has 138,000 rupees (11,5 euros) together.
What looks like a miserable reward for such a purely inhumane effort, however, is three times what he would earn from field work.
"The daily salary of the miners here, where 15,000 rupees (1,2 euros) per day are paid for coffee harvesting and the average monthly income is two million rupees (167 euros), is very high," explains the carrier, who previously worked as a maurer on the tourist island of Bali.
There he earned 75,000 rupees (6.2 euros) a day, and the work was not that hard, but Anto returned to Banyuwangi, a nearby village with his family, for a reason as important in Indonesia as sulfur: “I married a girl from Bali, where they are Hindu, and I brought her to Java to convert her to Islam.”
Anto has asthma, breathing with difficulty, coughing frequently and his eyes are irritated because of the toxic gases.
The 27-year-old Anto has been risking his life on Kawah Ijen for three years, whose sulfur has already left his first traces on him, even though he covers his face with a mask and special glasses.
Anto has asthma, breathing with difficulty, coughing frequently and his eyes are irritated because of the toxic gases from the volcano.
This is the price he has to pay to his dream.
"I will work here for two more years because I want to open a store or learn Spanish or French," he promises in more than acceptable English.
This sympathetic and intelligent but punished by life young man could work as a tourist guide, waitress, or at a hotel reception, but instead he does the job of a carrier.
He shares a dirty wooden cabin with other carriers and wakes up at two o’clock every morning because the sulfur also flows out at night, where its characteristic yellow color shines bluish in the dark.
Challenging the shadows, he climbs into the crater in the light of a small front lamp on his helmet, which he bought for his own money.
About 400 carriers load baskets of sulfur on their shoulders on the crater floor.
Despite its large profits, the mining company has not mechanized the mining of sulfur to save costs, and does not provide any equipment to operators who work on their own account and are paid by weight.
You will also not receive a share of the 30.000 rupees (2.5 euros) fee per camera, which the guard of this natural park, along with the entrance fee of 15,000 rupees (1,2 euros) from the tourists who come to photograph the volcano and the human bearing.
"This work is for the animals, not for man," protests Madrusin, a stumbling, 42-year-old carrier who has been working at Kawah Ijen for three decades since leaving school.
He is able to carry up to 110 kg and assures that he will continue "as long as possible" because he needs the money to raise his three children between the ages of 10 and 18.
I’m not going to retire, I’m going to die here because the volcano was my whole life.
Even when the sulfur burns the throat and the eyes itch, when the wind suddenly turns and clamps the miners in the thick columns rising from the crater, the men are so tough that nobody complains of serious illnesses ... of course except the usual breathing problems, arthrosis, pain in the knees and blisters on the shoulders that have been deformed by the weight of the baskets.
With the basket on his back, Unainik, 53 years old, is only able to carry 50 kg.
Every day, he and his companions break 15 tons of sulfur from the volcano, which is transported by three trucks over a goat path between the bush to the warehouse in Tamansari, 18 kilometers away.
"I'm not going to retire, I'm going to die here because the volcano was my whole life," Unainik explains, opening his mouth wide, in which some teeth are missing.
Of his five children, the eldest, at the age of 30, also works as a sulfur carrier.
Time goes by, but poverty holds generation after generation in one of the hardest professions in the world: the one of those who work as human burden seals at Kawah Ijen.
