Unasur summit ends without publication of Lima declaration
The 6th summit of the Presidents of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur) ended today in Peru without the publication of the Lima Declaration, which was previously announced and should theoretically be signed by the seven rulers present.
Efe has repeatedly attempted to gain access to the signed document at the 6th Ordinary Session of the Heads of State and Government of Unasur.Sources in the State and Presidential Office initially informed that they would hand it over after the clause, but subsequently stated that it would be published on the website of the Peruvian government at some time.
Asked about the text, they stated that the content was explained by Peruvian President Ollanta Humala in brief statements to the press.
Journalists’ access to information about the summit was limited at all times.
During the day, in the press room, only the image of the presidential meeting without sound was transmitted with the message "private session, limited audio".
The few information circulating among journalists were received from the press spokesmen of some of the Unasur governments present at the meeting, but not from the Peruvian press spokesman.
The only document spread during the day was the list of participating presidents, which caused discomfort among the hundreds of journalists from various national and international media calling for more information.
After that, the office of the Peruvian presidency sent an e-mail to the media containing the “final declaration” of the summit, but it was the declaration of Humala and not the official document concluding the summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the Third South America-Arab States Summit (ASPA), and even on this occasion, despite press calls, the so-called Lima Declaration, which was previously announced, was not published.
On the official website of the ASPA, one can be convinced that the document was published last Tuesday.
At both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities stressed that the information systems were available for journalists, but they severely restricted access to information.
The summit also ended with the joint commitment of Chile and Peru to accept a judgment of the Hague Court of Justice resolving a border conflict between the two countries.
The presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and Chile, Sebastián Piñera, met during the regional meeting and confirmed that they would accept the decision of the IGH, which begins in The Hague on Monday, in the trial that Lima initiated against Santiago, to listen to the claims of both sides.
“We will follow and execute the judgment on the differences that we are presenting to this International Court of Justice,” Humala and his Chilean counterpart said.
"Chile has been, is and will continue to be a country that adheres to international law, seeks peaceful solutions to disputes, makes agreements and submits itself to international courts," Piñera added, greeting Humala with a handshake before the flags of both countries.
The confirmation by both presidents that they would submit to the IGH came after Colombia filed a lawsuit against the Bogotá Agreement following a decision on the maritime borders with Nicaragua, which it considered a serious mistake, in which it agreed to submit to the judgments of that International Court of Justice.
At the summit were present the presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rouseff, of Venezuela, Hugo Chávez, of Bolivia, Evo Morales, and of Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, which has been excluded from Unasur since 2011 after the removal of its president Fernando Lugo, did not attend the meeting.
Host President Ollanta Humala opened the talks in the morning and concluded the summit shortly after lunch time in Lima.
The head of state read the final document, in which he announced that 16 decisions were made and the lines of action for 31 projects between the South American countries with a total investment of $17 billion were set.
On the decisions made, he said that the Unasur countries "will take significant steps towards the goal of South American citizenship, to which we extend the decisions on residence rights."
He said that measures would be pushed forward to “improve cooperation in the fight against urban uncertainty and organized, transnational crime, as well as measures to improve access to medicines and low-cost Internet in all areas of South America and to act jointly and efficiently in the event of natural disasters.”
With the crisis in Europe, "economic consolidation (in Latin America) must not take triumphant traits, but should serve to expand our production capacity and show our peoples a better future," Humala added.
“We have decided to prioritize a series of 31 emblematic projects aimed at improving spatial connections in South America and especially in rural and border areas... thus uniting our countries and uniting new forms of economy,” the Peruvian president said in a statement.
Among these projects would be five Peruvian, located on the cross-axis of its territory from the coast to Brazil, and of which two are meant to provide a better connection with Ecuador, although he did not provide further details.
The final document also referred to the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that the election process in this country serves to re-enter it in the Union of South American Nations," from which it is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America to continue to be an integrated region of prosperity and peace and with good neighbourly relations was another aspect that was emphasized at the summit.
In this sense, the President of Colombia, Juan Manuel Santos, said before starting his participation in the regional meeting that he expected a meeting with his Nicaraguan counterpart, Daniel Ortega, on Saturday in Mexico to respectfully deal with the maritime conflict following a ruling of the IGH challenged by Bogotá.
“I’ll probably meet with President Daniel Ortega tomorrow,” Santos said.
"We will review all these routes - they are not exclusive, and even the agreement with Nicaragua makes talks with Nicaragua necessary," he stressed.
"I hope to be able to tell President Ortega that we will deal with this matter as civilised and respectful as possible," Santos said.
Santos and Ortega are scheduled to meet in Mexico on Saturday, where they intend to attend the inauguration of the new president of that country, Enrique Peña Nieto.
As part of the summit, the defence ministers of the bloc also met in advance to adopt the 2013 action plan to strengthen dialogue and consensus on defence in the region.
Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Surinam and Paraguay are members of UNASUR, although the latter is currently excluded.
Peru holds the presidency for the period of the regional bloc.
