Fabrizio was 21 years old when the test confirmed he was HIV positive.
"It was like a bomb was hitting," he says about the moment he received the diagnosis that the doctor tried to "weaken" without noticeable success.
He hid it from his family.
He decided to take care of his illness alone and began to learn about it; and this with such dedication that he was just celebrating his 43rd birthday.
He is undoubtedly one of the oldest patients in the HIV unit of the Hospital Civil de Guadalajara (HCG), to which he came after several battles in 1994.
Fabrizio has been living with the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) for 22 years, which was hard to imagine in the early 1990s when there were many doubts, few treatment options and more stigma.
At that time, even the director of an IMSS clinic avoided saying goodbye, "because it led to an impasse."
AIDS was synonymous with death.
Today, it is possible to survive this syndrome even with quality of life.
However, still many people come to the clinic who know nothing about their disease and in whom the virus has already done harm and exhausted their immune system, and are victims of opportunistic infections.
31 years after the emergence of AIDS in the world, i.e. after the appearance of the first cases, "the great success today means that the survival of a patient who starts treatment in time and the survival of the general population are exactly the same," explained the head of the HIV unit of HCG, Jaime Andrade Villanueva, saying that this information was backed up by a prestigious scientific publication in April of this year.
Andrade Villanueva, an expert on infectious diseases and HIV/AIDS, commented that scientists have concluded since 2008 that while AIDS is not a death sentence, the years of survival and quality of life depend on the degree of impairment of the people’s immune system at the start of treatment, and that those who are not drug addicts have greater chances: up to 30 years with a count of 200 CD4 and 50 years with a count of 500 CD4.
Simply put, the above statements mean that anyone who gets the diagnosis of being HIV-positive at the age of 25 can, in this sense, "problemlessly reach 75 years of age as long as he is under control," this expert explained.
To correctly classify this progress, it must be remembered that the average life expectancy of Mexicans today is 76 years.
Even though mortality has decreased significantly in recent years (in Mexico, the number of people dying from AIDS has decreased from 6,678 cases in 2007 to 4,862 in 2011), it is still true that since the emergence of AIDS, 60 percent of the patients recorded in the national database have died.
In Jalisco alone, 255 people died in 2011, and by May this year there were already 187 deaths; however, it is assured that there has been universal access to antiretroviral drugs since 2005.
So why are people still dying from it?
The problem is not access to treatment.
This is my opinion, and so is in our hospital.
At least in the last 12 years we have not had any problems with the supply of the drugs.The problem is that people come in a very advanced state because they do not know their infection state, i.e. in very late stages of the disease.
He makes a striking statement: “Nine out of ten patients come to us when they already have an accompanying infection.In order to influence global mortality, earlier diagnosis is needed, which is why massive detection tests must be offered to all those who need it.”
This proposal is supported by experts and officials of the Consejo Estatal de Prevención del Sida en Jalisco (Coesida) (State Committee on AIDS Prevention in Jalisco) and also by patients such as Fabrizio, who made his test in a private laboratory, and this for the sole reason that it had made a friend of him who, despite his young age, was already in the AIDS phase and even had the Kaposi sarcoma (a cancer-like tumor), which is one of the common complications.
Everything is different when you know you have AIDS.
Some think they’re going to die and don’t want to hear anything.
“If I have to die, I’d rather break three times,” they say.
The change was to improve, I eat well, do sports and take the medications.
Today, his parents only know that he had cancer.
I live a normal life, like everyone else.
“I work, I do a lot, I have an active but responsible sex life, I take care of my health and that of the other person,” says Fabrizio, who agreed to share his intimate details with MILENIO JALISCO to animate with his testimony those who are afraid today as part of the World AIDS Day.
The sooner they know if they are HIV positive, the better, and if they already know the diagnosis, they should learn how to live responsibly like all people.
His message is a summary of the fight against AIDS in 2012.
Condoms behind the table
There are huge gaps between health programs and the common citizen, explains Ricardo Salazar, a journalist from Guadalajara who has taken on the cause of HIV.
The most important thing is prevention.
“The distribution of condoms was actually increased; before they were handed out individually, now they give us packages with a hundred pieces, which is good, but there are still people who don’t have access to a condom,” he said.
Among the people at risk for new infections are young people.
"Why do you need it?" is a widespread mocking question from social workers, school orientation staff, pharmacy employees, and the healthcare system that young people don't want to expose themselves to, the correspondent assured.
He proposed reorienting this inefficient distribution; the condoms should be placed not only behind the counter table, but in output devices in public toilets of establishments frequently visited by young people.
It is not to promote promiscuity.
They are not to be paid for the beer and motel, as Governor Emilio González responded to the question of whether condoms would be distributed under his administration.
“Sexuality doesn’t look like that; it’s best to bring condoms closer to those who are already engaged in sexual activity,” he said.
Key data from Jalisco
There are 13,435 accumulated cases (12,158 AIDS and 1,317 HIV).
The state ranks fourth nationally for new and cumulative cases of AIDS, and thirteenth in terms of HIV.
92% of infections occur through sexual intercourse, 6% through blood, and 2% perinatal.
It is estimated that 50,000 people live with HIV because for every registered case there are 4 or 5 people who don’t know about it.
